{ Welcome to the Quickstarter!   In this chapter you will have a summary with the necessary lines to familiarize yourself with the content of the course, and thus be able to use it in your games immediately. }
1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dynamically in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nge2
{ in order to go for the English attack system. White is ready to capture on d4 with the knight. }
4... Be7 5. f3
{ prophylaxis against Ng4. Now the bishop can be developed to e3 without troubles. }
5... O-O 6. Be3
{ And here we are going to suggest two paths to proceed.  6...c6  is the first suggestion from Stockfish and  6...exd4  is a line where white can fall in many tricks and the one that I have employed myself in all my games so far. }
6... exd4
{ With this move, we are hoping that white recaptures with the knight, because the position gets wild and in most cases favourable for black. And believe me, white will go for Nxd4 in many many cases! }
7. Nxd4 d5
{ this is the whole point. Black uses the fact that white's king is still in the center to open the e-file }
8. e5
{ This move looks annoying but in fact white is the one that has to be extremely precise from this point. We can follow two interesting paths now }
8... c5
{ This is the move that I have employed myself in several games. It is very strong as well. It was during the preparation of this series when I discovered that engines prefer a little bit more 8... Ne8!. Black regains the piece using the fork on d4   8...Ne8  This is the best move according to the engine. Black is threatening to pusch c5 and win a piece!  9.Be2  c5  10.Nb3  d4 }
9. exf6 { 9.Ndb5  d4  10.exf6  transposes } 9... Bxf6 10. Be2 Re8
{ Interesting too. It is the move that I have played in classical time control, but the engine finds a nice novelty for white to equalize. }
11. Ndb5 *

