{ Welcome to the Quickstarter! } 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5.
Qxd8+
{ We devote a whole chapter to study the Philidor endgame.   It is not the most critical line that white can try against the Philidor, and some people tend to think that the position is very drawish, but I think this is far from true. The position is very interesting and both sides can play for the win.   Usually Philidor players feel comfortable with the endgame. I have played myself this endgame in 16 classical games and only got two draws!.   Usually, these games tend to be very long, and we have to be ready to fight! But that is what we are here for!  Last but not least, for this particular chapter, I strongly recommend you to check the analyzed games in the last part of this series so you see how to play and 'feel' this positions after studying the theory. }
5... Kxd8 6. Bc4 { Our approach is going to be the most aggresive one with }
6... Bb4
{ It is a move that has not been played much compared to the main lines, so you will probably surprise your opponent in many cases.  6...Be6  or  6...Ke8  are the main lines. }
7. f3
{ and here and I am going to suggest you a variation that it has not been played much according to my database. Nevertheless, I have huge experience with it, having employed it in dozens of rapid and blitz games and in couple of classical games. }
7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6
{ reaching this very strange looking position. In practice, black's play is very easy and all the time focused on the c4 square. But of course, white has a better pawn structure. At the end of the series, I will analyze 5 games that I have played in this line. }
10. Nh3 { 10.Be3  or  10.Rb1  are also reasonable moves for white. } 10... Nbd7
{ more precise than Nc6. In many occasions black rook can be activated on the third rank by playing a5. With a knight on c6, this would not be possible. }
11. Ke2
{ was played in Backwinkel,P @@StartBracket@@2410@@EndBracket@@-Tischbierek,R @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Germany 1994 }
11... a5 12. Nf2 Ne8
{ and our plan is the same: bringing a knight to d6 and a rook to a6. } *

