{  } 1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dinamycally in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+
{ We devote a whole chapter to study the Philidor endgame.   It is not the most critical line that white can try against the Philidor, and some people tend to think that the position is very drawish, but I think this is far from true. The position is very interesting and both sides can play for the win.   Usually Philidor players feel comfortable with the endgame. I have played myself this endgame in 16 classical games and only got two draws!.   Usually, these games tend to be very long, and we have to be ready to fight! But that is what we are here for!  Last but not least, for this particular chapter, I strongly recommend you to check the analyzed games in the last part of this series so you see how to play and 'feel' this positions after studying the theory. }
5... Kxd8 6. Bg5
{ Probably the most natural move in this position. White pins the knight and is ready to castle long winning another tempo. Now we propose two ways to play. }
6... Be6
{ This is the most solid approach for black. Black's idea is to develop the knight to d7 later. The Bishop on e6 does a great job covering f7. }
7. O-O-O+ Nd7 8. f4
{ This is the critical line. White goes for the direct approach. It is important to remember all these lines and understand the ideas properly. }
8... exf4 9. Nf3 Kc8 10. Bxf4
{ Black has to be very careful now because Nb5 is a strong idea. Transposes to the main line }
10... Bc5
{ Prophylaxis against Nb5, If  10...Ng4?!  11.Nb5!  Nf2  12.Nxc7  Nxh1  13.Nxa8  Nf2  14.Re1+= }
11. h3
{ Prophylaxis against Ng4. It is the most played move by far and not the most dangerous, which is good news! }
11... Nh5 12. Bh2 Be3+ 13. Kb1 Bf4 14. Bxf4 Nxf4
{ This way, again we have managed to 'gain' control on the e5 square by eliminating the dark squared bishop. Black has good play against g3 or Nd4, by bringing the knight to g6 and then to e5 and went on to win in Kravtsiv,M @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@-Khismatullin, D @@StartBracket@@2632@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Riadh 2017 Philidor endgame @@StartSquare@@Pepe@@EndSquare@@ }
*

