{ Welcome to the Quickstarter!   In this chapter you will have a summary with the necessary lines to familiarize yourself with the content of the course, and thus be able to use it in your games immediately. }
1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze in deep the sharpest line of the Philidor with 4...exd4.   White will play 6.Bf4 to follow with Qd2 and O-O-O. To be completely honest with you, this chapter has given me a constant headache for a couple of weeks.   Wesley So, in his e4 Lifetime Repertoires series for Chessable, dedicates five chapters to the Philidor. His analysis of course is world-class and his preparation is amazing. He actually recommends 6.Bf4. The lines he shows against our beloved defense are great and I have been several nights trying to find the best way to deal with it.  After more than 30 hours of research, I found a line that in my opinion equalizes. This is probably one of the most important chapters from the theoretical point of view, and supercomputers are needed to refine the lines until the end.   This means these lines are tested with depth at least 45-50 in Stockfish 12.   Lines are exciting and hard to understand, but as usual in turbulent waters, if we come to the game with the home analysis learned, it will be our opponent the one who will struggle to find the right moves.   Fasten your seatbelts because some curves are coming! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7
6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the main line with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... d5
{ Striking in the center already. This move has been played by several strong Grandmasters and leads to huge complications. It is a good surprising weapon.   When I was preparing this series, my first intention was to recommend  7...c6  , a very agressive move employed by non other than Magnus Carlsen in 2020 against Leinier Domínguez, but I could not fully equalize after  8.O-O-O  b5  9.f3  b4  10.Na4! }
8. Ndb5
{ The main line by far. 204 games in my database while only less than 30 with  8.e5  and  8.O-O-O  . White targets c7 and the d5 pawn. }
8... Bb4 { and the party starts. } 9. O-O-O { the main line by far. } 9... c6
10. Nc7
{ This is all forced. We have to be ready to sacrifice a rook. Who dares to say that the Philidor is boring? Let's party! }
10... Nxe4
{ and now white has two possibilities and both have been played more or less the same. Black is using all it can against the white king. We have to take in account that our a8 rook is completely lost. }
11. Qe3
{ If you are checking this line with the engine, it will say +1.50 at the begginning. You have to let it run till depth 45-60 and will say 0.00. That is why supercomputers are so important nowadays in critical lines. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Na6 { we need to get some pieces out! } 14.
Bxa6 bxa6 15. Nxa8 Qa5 { TR } *

