11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Na6 { we need to get some pieces out! } 14.
Nxa8 { 14.Bxa6  bxa6  15.Nxa8  Qa5  transposes } 14... Qa5
{ now white has tried three different alternatives. } 15. Bxa6
{ The main continuation. White connects the rooks and eliminates a dangerous knight. In return black gets an open b-file and the b5 square is not covered now. }
15... bxa6 { Black threatens mate in two: Qb5+ and Qb2++ TR } 16. Ka1
{ White hides the king and now has the possibility to bring a rook to the b-file covering the focal point b2. That is why black looks for a new focal point which is going to be a2. }
16... Be6 { d4 is in the air. Now five different moves have been tried. } 17.
Qe5
{ is strongly met with   17.Nc7  happened in Kotronias,V @@StartBracket@@2613@@EndBracket@@-De la Villa Garcia,J @@StartBracket@@2472@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Benasque 2009 and black is better after d4. We will examine this game deeply in the 'model games' final chapter.  d4  18.Rxd4  Bc1   17.Qd3  prophylaxis against d4.  Rxa8  18.Rhe1  Qa4!?  or 18...Bf5 interesting to play for the win.  19.Qd2 Be6 20.Qd3  and we reach this strange repetition. }
17... Be7 { @@StartBracket@@threatening Bf6@@EndBracket@@ } 18. Bd2 Rxa8
{ and black is better. Piece + pawn + bishop pair + safer king vs rook is good business for black! }
*

