{ Welcome back to a new chapter!   This is probably the wildest one in the whole course.   White goes for an extremely aggressive approach with 5.g4!?, a move that came into fashion thanks to Alexey Shirov, who employed it for the first time in 2003 against Azmaiparashvili. Since then, it became very popular and has been tried by many players against the Philidor.   It has a lot of venom and we should really know what to do with the black pieces. I have worked very hard and found different novelties that hopefully will help you.   Hope you enjoy all the crazy variations that are going to arise! }
1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dinamycally in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ Straight to the jugular vein. White sacrifices a pawn and will get a lot of counterplay along the g-file, making difficult for black to develop the f8-bishop in many variations. Black should take the pawn }
5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6
{ and from this point we divide the chapter into two parts. We first analyze the lines where white goes 7.Bc4 and then the lines where white does not play 7.Bc4 and instead try to develop fast the queenside. Both are very dangerous. }
7. Bc4 { 7.Be3  White's idea is to play  Qc2  and  O-O-O } 7... exd4
{ Our second recommendation. This capture has been played by two gods of the Philidor defence: GM Strikovic and GM Paunovic. Black frees the e5 square for the knight. }
*

