[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Philidor Shirov 5.g4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome back to a new chapter!   This is probably the wildest one in the whole course.   White goes for an extremely aggressive approach with 5.g4!?, a move that came into fashion thanks to Alexey Shirov, who employed it for the first time in 2003 against Azmaiparashvili. Since then, it became very popular and has been tried by many players against the Philidor.   It has a lot of venom and we should really know what to do with the black pieces. I have worked very hard and found different novelties that hopefully will help you.   Hope you enjoy all the crazy variations that are going to arise! }
1. e4 { - } 1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 Nbd7
5. g4
{ Straight to the jugular vein. White sacrifices a pawn and will get a lot of counterplay along the g-file, making difficult for black to develop the f8-bishop in many variations. Black should take the pawn }
5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6
{ and from this point we divide the chapter into two parts. We first analyze the lines where white goes 7.Bc4 and then the lines where white does not play 7.Bc4 and instead try to develop fast the queenside. Both are very dangerous. }
7. Bc4
{ Perhaps the most natural move. White is already threatening to win with the move Ng5 because f7 suffers. Now we give two interesting alternatives for black. }
7... h6 { Prophylaxis against Ng5. The main line by far. } 8. Be3
{ White starts developing the queenside, because its short term plan is to castle longside. Black will struggle developing the kingside because of the pressure along the g-file. That is why black main moves will be focused on the queenside. }
8... c6
{ a very typical move that we have seen many times. Black controls d5, and prepares an expansion on the queenside with b5. }
9. dxe5
{ The main line.   9.Qd3  The queen on d3 makes more sense than on d2. First of all, protects e4 and after some black's b4, the queen could come to c4 targetting f7, as we will see in some crazy lines.  b5  10.Bb3  Qa5  the queen on a5 is well placed. It protects the a6 square, where a bishop will land. That means that b4 will be a real threat in such positions.  11.dxe5  Transpose to the main line. }
9... dxe5 10. Qd3 { white protects the e4-pawn and is ready to castle. } 10...
b5 11. Bxf7+
{ I am 100% sure that many of you will face this move in practice many times. In my case, I have played at least 10 times this position in rapid tournaments. This capture on f7 is very tempting for white because white gets a queen, but black gets enough material for the queen and objetively will be better.   11.Bb3  Qa5  12.O-O-O  Ba6  Transposes to the lines analyzed with 9.Qd3. We arrive to the end of the chapter. This is probably the one that I enjoyed the most preparing this series. It is always nice to see some crazy lines and of course even nicer to realise that black holds. See you in the next one and if you drink do not drive! }
11... Kxf7 12. Nxe5+ Nxe5 13. Qxd8 Nf3+
{ this is the point. Black gets the rook in g1 as well. } 14. Kd1 Nxg1
{ Too fast Pepe! Let's count the pieces. Black has a rook and two pieces for the queen, which is more than enough. Still the position is complicated so we will have to make couple of precise moves to consolidate our advantage. }
15. Kc1 { The king hides   15.Qc7+  Be7  16.Kc1  transposes } 15... Be7
{ This is the key! Fast development of our backrank pieces and if white captues on h8, then the queen will end up trapped. }
16. Qc7 { the most active move, targetting c6. } 16... Bg4
{ completing development and also aiming to go Ne2+ exchanging the forgotten g1 knight. }
17. Bc5 Rhe8 18. a4 b4
{ It is important to close the a-file so the rook on a1 remains sad and single. }
19. Bxb4 c5 20. Bxc5 Rac8 21. Qg3 Bxc5 22. Qxg1 Bh5
{ black is winning. We had to sacrifice two pawns but now our king will be very safe on g8 and the two bishops will be killing knives. }
*

