{ Welcome to the Quickstarter!   In this chapter you will have a summary with the necessary lines to familiarize yourself with the content of the course, and thus be able to use it in your games immediately. }
1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dinamycally in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone! Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7. That means white goes for short castle, followed by Re1 and a4. Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a big number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here. I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 { Remember that white can also start with } 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O
{ transposing. } 7... c6 8. Qe2
{ New chapter!   How is your energy battery? Hope still some power left!   On this occasion, we focus on this 8.Qe2 line. There are more than 400 games with this line in my database, therefore deserves serious attention.   White's idea is to free the d1-square for the rook. This line brings me good memories because I won a very important game with the black pieces and took clear first in 'La Roda' Open in 2011, probably one of the most important tournament victories in my career.   Whenever there is a queen on e2, it is interesting to open the e-file and put pressure on e4. That is why we play }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8
{ the idea is to place the bishop on f8 and put pressure on e4. d5 is a very typical reaction in these positions. }
10. Ba2 { The main line by far. It is a good prophylactic move against d5. }
10... Bf8 { and guess what? Yes, d5 is the idea. } 11. Qf3
{ White removes the queen from the e-file and keeps protecting the e4 pawn. Now we advocate two possibilities to continue. One is the main line and the second one is a super interesting novelty. }
11... Ne5 { The main line, activating the knight and hitting the queen. } 12.
Qd1
{ 12.Qg3  is another option with two alternatives that we will look at. This is the main line by far. White's queen will be safe in this variation.   And again I give two possibilities.  12...Ng6  which is more solid and 'Philidor style' and  12...a5  which can lead to complications. }
12... a5 { es la otra que damos } *

