{ Welcome to the Quickstarter!   In this chapter you will have a summary with the necessary lines to familiarize yourself with the content of the course, and thus be able to use it in your games immediately. }
1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dinamycally in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone! Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7. That means white goes for short castle, followed by Re1 and a4. Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a big number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here. I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 { Remember that white can also start with } 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... b6
{ This is the main line by far and a move that I have been in love with since I was a kid. I played more than 50 classical games with this line, but modern theory has shown that black cannot fully equalize in my opinion. The line that annoys me the most is the following: }
9. Ba2 a6 10. h3 Rb8 11. Be3 b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. b4
{ and I tried very hard to find something suitable for black in the last 2-3 years but I think white is just better. }
*

