{ Welcome to the Quickstarter!   In this chapter you will have a summary with the necessary lines to familiarize yourself with the content of the course, and thus be able to use it in your games immediately. }
1. e4
{ In this section we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3 and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the king side. Black must react dinamycally in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players. And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line.  Many opponents will fall for traps we have prepared. Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 { Remember that white can also start with } 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ which is a secondary line. Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it. There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid. Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move. White has four main choices now. }
9. Ba2
{ a very typical move, hiding the bishop in a safe square. It is a profilactic move against d5, b5 or even Nb6 ideas at some point. }
9... Re8 10. h3
{ The main line.   In fact we can reach this position as well after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbpp1/2pp1n1p/4p3/P1BPP3/2N2N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  Re8  10.Ba2  . White covers the g4 square so a bishop can land on e3 without troubles. is the main line and transposes to what we have analyzed after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbpp1/2pp1n1p/4p3/P1BPP3/2N2N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ba2  followed by 10.h3 }
10... a5 { black fixes the structure on the queenside. } 11. Be3
{ This is the same position that Wesley So covers in his series but the white queen is on e2 and the bishop is on c4. That tempo that white has lost by moving the bishop is very important for black! }
11... exd4
{ a secondary line but the best move!   11...Qc7  is the main line by far. }
12. Nxd4 Bf8
{ improving the bishop and putting pressure on e4. White has tried four different moves now: }
13. Bf4
{ white protects e4 and starts putting pressure on d6. Now black has two decent choices. }
13... Nc5
{ 13...Ra6!?  is a very interesting move that you can try as well, intending Rb6-Rb4. }
14. Qf3
{ the main line. There are twelve games in my database and some of them are played by GMs. TR }
14... Ne6 { and white has tried three moves at this point: } 15. Nxe6
{ A massive trade on e6 is harmless for black. } 15... Bxe6 16. Bxe6 Rxe6 17.
Rad1
{ following Sadikhov,U @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@-Kacharava,N @@StartBracket@@2437@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ playchess.com 2020 and I suggest you to play }
17... Qe8
{ increasing the pressure on e4. Black has good play with ideas such as Nd7-Nc5-Rd8. }
