1. e4 d6 2. g3
{ Hi all!   Here we are in a new chapter.   As I have told you, anything that is not  2.d4  is not critical from the theoretical point of view but 2.g3 is a very flexible move.   Black has several reasonable ways to continue now.   If we play  2...c5  , we will probably enter in closed Sicilian positions.  2...e5  is a possibility as well that could even transpose to other chapters of the course, but I am going to recommend you a very direct approach where we are aiming to transpose to a good version of the Scandinavian defense. }
2... d5
{ This move is also the first recommendation from Stockfish 12. Black has 'lost' a tempo by playing d5 in two moves but white has also committed on the kingside by playing g3.   That means that there will pressure on the main diagonal and Bg4 will be coming very fast to annoy a knight on f3.  White has tried different options here but the strongest move is }
3. e5
{ is already pretty dubious. The e5 pawn will be in a bad situation after }
3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bg2 Bg4 { and e5 is already suffering. } 6. h3 Bxf3 7.
Qxf3 e6
{ Once d5 is protected, Nxe5 is the next move if white does not protect it. }
8. Qe2 Qc7 9. f4 Nge7 10. c3
{ Happened Di Lascio,S @@StartBracket@@2012@@EndBracket@@-Gatterer,F @@StartBracket@@2323@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Bergamo 2009 and Black has a decisive advantage after the cool }
10... g5
{ Boom!   Black will take on f4 and install a fantastic knight on f5. Once the g-file is opened, the white king will not be comfortable on the kingside. }
*

