1. e4 d6 2. g3
{ Hi all!   Here we are in a new chapter.   As I have told you, anything that is not  2.d4  is not critical from the theoretical point of view but 2.g3 is a very flexible move.   Black has several reasonable ways to continue now.   If we play  2...c5  , we will probably enter in closed Sicilian positions.  2...e5  is a possibility as well that could even transpose to other chapters of the course, but I am going to recommend you a very direct approach where we are aiming to transpose to a good version of the Scandinavian defense. }
2... d5
{ This move is also the first recommendation from Stockfish 12. Black has 'lost' a tempo by playing d5 in two moves but white has also committed on the kingside by playing g3.   That means that there will pressure on the main diagonal and Bg4 will be coming very fast to annoy a knight on f3.  White has tried different options here but the strongest move is }
3. exd5 Qxd5 { White has now two ways to protect the h1 rook. } 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ And White has two choices now. The most natural is } 5. Be2
{ Since White does not lose the right to castle. GM Pantoja played it in two games.   The idea is to avoid  5...Qe6+ }
5... Nc6 { And White must play precisely } 6. h3 Bh5
{ and GM Munoz Pantoja chose two moves at this crossroads. We deeply analyze both options. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. d4
{ White needs to control the center. This was seen in Munoz Pantoja,M @@StartBracket@@2442@@EndBracket@@ -Narciso Dublan,M @@StartBracket@@2492@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Barbera del Valles 2020 and I recommend you to play the aggresive move }
8... h5
{ White has now two natural ways of winning a tempo by hitting the queen. } 9.
c4 { The best move in my opinion gaining a lot of space in the center. } 9...
Qd6 10. g5 { White needs to do something about the opening of the h-file. }
10... e6 11. Nc3 O-O-O { attacking d4. } 12. Be3 Nge7
{ There we go! Black intends Nf5 putting a lot of pressure against d4 and e3. }
13. c5
{ The best move. White weakens the d5-square but at the same time will try to create troubles along the a4-e8 diagonal. }
13... Qd7 14. Qa4 Nd5 { White gave us the square so we should go for it! } 15.
O-O-O Be7 16. Bb5 { Once again, White intends to play Ne5. } 16... f6
{ And White should act quickly since positionally is worse. } 17. Rhg1
{ White threatens gxf6 followed by Rxg6. } 17... Be8 18. gxf6 gxf6 19. Rg7
{ and we reach an endgame after } 19... a6 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Qxc6 Bxc6 22. Nxd5
Bxd5 23. Rxe7 { Otherwise Black will play Bf8 and enjoy the bishop pair. }
23... Bxf3 24. Rg1 Rde8
{ Black chases the rook since it cannot allow a second rook on the 7th rank, what would be fatal for Black. }
25. Rf7 Rhf8 26. Rxf8 Rxf8 27. Rg7 e5
{ And Black should hold without much problems.   One idea is to play Bd5 followed by Rf7. }
