[Black "Philidor 2.c4 e5 3.Nf3 c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter, we cover the move  1...--  2.c4  . White may want to continue with  --  3.d4  occupying all the center or go for the Botvinnik System @@StartBracket@@Nc3, g3, Bg2, Nge2, etc.@@EndBracket@@.   I have found very interesting and aggressive recipes, so no more talk and let's go straight to the point! }
1... d6 2. c4 e5
{ Once we have played this move, black should avoid arriving to Maroczy-type positions and that means stopping white to play d4 followed by Nxf3. At this point, white has three options.   Some people will try  3.Nf3  aiming to go for  --  4.d4  . Others will go for the Botvinnik System and another bunch of people will try  3.d4  straightaway. }
3. Nf3 { I recommend you to play the strong move } 3... c5
{ and I would say this is already a bit more comfortable in practice for black. f4 and f5 are breaking points and the knight on f3 is pretty clumsy stopping this reaction.   On the other hand, black will play Nc6, g6, Bg7, Nge7, O-O and f5 will be coming very easily. White can play on the queenside with b4 at some point or can try to remove the f3-knight to push f4.   Of course, d5 is also a tasty square for white. }
4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d3 g6 6. Nd5 { This move does not interfere with our plans. }
6... Bg7 7. Be2 Nge7 8. Bg5
{ 8.O-O  transposes to the lines analyzed after 6.Be2. } 8... h6
{ and at this crossroads, white has tried two different moves. } 9. Bf6
{ 9.Bxe7  Nxe7=+  . Black is better due to the bishop pair. White has not achieved anything in return.   The maneuver was very poor. }
9... Bxf6 10. Nxf6+ Kf8
{ black intends to play Kg7 kicking the knight from f6. } 11. O-O
{ 11.Nd5  Kg7  12.O-O  transposes. } 11... Kg7 12. Nd5
{ was seen in Belenov,D @@StartBracket@@2303@@EndBracket@@-Dzhakaev,D @@StartBracket@@2445@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Krasnodar 2003 and we suggest to continue with }
12... Rf8 { Black has castled artificially already. } 13. Rb1 a5 14. a3 Bd7
{ White struggles to play b4, since, after the trades on b4 and d5, the b4-pawn falls. }
15. Qd2 f5
{ with very easy play for Black and good attacking chances on the kingside. } *

