{ Once we have played this move, black should avoid arriving to Maroczy-type positions and that means stopping white to play d4 followed by Nxf3. At this point, white has three options.   Some people will try  3.Nf3  aiming to go for  --  4.d4  . Others will go for the Botvinnik System and another bunch of people will try  3.d4  straightaway. }
3. d4
{ White goes for a Maroczy set-up. The drawback of course is that black will win a tempo by hitting the queen after Nc6. }
3... exd4 4. Qxd4
{ White should take otherwise c5 will protect the pawn for good. } 4... Nc6 5.
Qe3 { has been tried in several games. } 5... g6 6. Bd2
{ This is white's idea, bringing the bishop to c3 to fight against the g7-bishop. It is too slow and white has moved twice the queen and twice the bishop. If Capablanca rose from the grave! }
6... Bg7 7. Bc3 Nf6
{ this is the key! not allowing the trade of bishops. Now black's plan is very simple: bringing a rook to e8 and strike with d5. White has tried three moves. }
8. Bd3 O-O 9. f3 Re8 10. Ne2 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Qd2 Nxc3
{ and black had a decisive advantage in Rakic,M @@StartBracket@@2128@@EndBracket@@-Chilingirova,P @@StartBracket@@2209@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Vratsa 2006. Idea: Ne5 followed by c6. The dark squares are simply too weak. }
