1. e4
{ In this chapter, we cover the move  1...--  2.c4  . White may want to continue with  --  3.d4  occupying all the center or go for the Botvinnik System @@StartBracket@@Nc3, g3, Bg2, Nge2, etc.@@EndBracket@@.   I have found very interesting and aggressive recipes, so no more talk and let's go straight to the point! }
1... d6 2. c4 e5
{ Once we have played this move, black should avoid arriving to Maroczy-type positions and that means stopping white to play d4 followed by Nxf3. At this point, white has three options.   Some people will try  3.Nf3  aiming to go for  --  4.d4  . Others will go for the Botvinnik System and another bunch of people will try  3.d4  straightaway. }
3. d4
{ White goes for a Maroczy set-up. The drawback of course is that black will win a tempo by hitting the queen after Nc6. }
3... exd4 4. Qxd4
{ White should take otherwise c5 will protect the pawn for good. } 4... Nc6 5.
Qd1 f5
{ This aggresive move is 'setting a trap' because white's most natural reaction is dubious.   5...g6  is of course also playable. }
6. exf5 Bxf5
{ and when I was analyzing over the board this position when preparing this series, my first instinct was to play }
7. Bd3
{ which is innacurate! We tend to exchange light squared bishops when black has weakened the light squares by playing f5. In fact in the only two games with this position, white went for this move. }
7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 d5
{ This is the point! Black opens the position up. The b4 square will be importat in the resulting variations. }
9. Nf3 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Qe7+ 11. Kf1 dxc4 12. Qxc4 Nf6
{ and black long castles next move and it is better because of the kings situation. }
