[White "3. Philidor 2.Bc4"]
[Black "Philidor 2.Bc4 Nf6 3.d3 e6 4.Bb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. Bc4
{ Hi all!   In this new chapter, we cover 2.Bc4. In my opinion, it is a harmless move and black gets very healthy positions from the very beginning.   Black has not defined the structure on the center with e5 yet, so since that the bishop is on c4, we will go for an early e6 followed by d5, winning tempo and neutralizing the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... Nf6 3. d3 { This move does not change our plan. } 3... e6 4. Bb3
{ profilaxis against d5. Of course, there are many valid different ways to proceed from here but the one I like is }
4... b5 { gaining space on the queenside. } 5. Nf3 Be7 6. O-O c5 7. c3 a5
{ Black continues the expansion. } 8. a4 b4 9. Re1 O-O 10. Nbd2 Ba6
{ And Black have a very good play.   Ideas: Nc6, Qc7. In certain positions, Ne5 will be a possibility allowing white to double our pawns but at the same time, black gets nice counterplay along the d-file and against d3. }
*

