1. e4 d6 2. Bc4
{ Hi all!   In this new chapter, we cover 2.Bc4. In my opinion, it is a harmless move and black gets very healthy positions from the very beginning.   Black has not defined the structure on the center with e5 yet, so since that the bishop is on c4, we will go for an early e6 followed by d5, winning tempo and neutralizing the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 e6
{ 3...e5  would be an attempt to transpose to our beloved Philidor, but white is not forced to play  4.Nf3  and can go for  4.d3  Be7  and  5.f4  leading to Vienna type positions. }
4. d3 d5
{ Ocassionally life is beautiful and black is already slightly better after move 4. This is the problem when white does not go for the critical lines @@StartBracket@@i.e. 2.d4@@EndBracket@@. Sometimes black can equalize very easily or even get a better position, but of course, we are not going to complain about that! }
5. Bb3 dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1
{ and black have a slightly more pleasant endgame given the white king situation. This was seen in Zimmer, R  @@StartBracket@@2122@@EndBracket@@-Henrich, D @@StartBracket@@2092@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Sasbach 2018 and I recommend following with }
7... Nc6 8. Nge2 a6 9. f3 Nd7 10. Be3 b5
{ black has fantastic play with Nce5 followed by c5. } *

