1. e4
{ Hi all!   Hope you recharged your batteries for this new chapter!   In this case, we cover the lines where white starts with  2.f4  or  2.Nc3  .  Sometimes it leads to positions that have many similarities with the King's Gambit, Vienna Gambit or even closed Sicilians. }
1... d6 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 e5
{ and with this move, if white plays d4 at some point, we would be transposing to lines covered in other chapters, so we just need to analyze variations where White plays d3 instead of d4. }
4. Bg2 Be7 5. d3 { White can start with  5.Nf3  or  5.Nge2  and then play d3. }
5... O-O 6. Nge2
{ Makes more sense to me than  6.Nf3  . White prepares short castling and f4. }
6... c6 7. O-O b5 { we do not change plans. } 8. a3 a5 9. h3 Nbd7
{ and now we analyze four options that White has tried } 10. f4
{ The most frequently played move, and also the most aggressive. } 10... Ra6
{ Black gets ready to push b4. } 11. f5 b4 12. Nb1 d5
{ As everyone says, whenever your opponent attacks you on a flank, react in the center! }
13. Nd2 dxe4 14. dxe4 h6
{ And suddenly the rook on a6 is fantastically placed since Black wants to play c5 followed by Rd6 and Bb7 or Ba6! }
