1. e4
{ Hi all!   Hope you recharged your batteries for this new chapter!   In this case, we cover the lines where white starts with  2.f4  or  2.Nc3  .  Sometimes it leads to positions that have many similarities with the King's Gambit, Vienna Gambit or even closed Sicilians. }
1... d6 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ I have faced this line several times, including a game against Armenian GM Andriasian.   This is an important crossroads where I will give you two different paths to follow. One of them will be the move 3...c5, transposing to a Sicilian @@StartBracket@@usually Grand Prix, which is not considered to be very dangerous@@EndBracket@@.   And the other option is the move  3...e5  , in a more Philidor style that sometimes can even transpose to King's Gambit positions. Both are deeply analyzed, so you have to choose what you prefer :@@EndBracket@@   3.Bc4  transposes to the 2.Bc4 chapter. 3.Nf3  transposes to the 2.Nf3 chapter. }
3... c5
{ Most of the times, White will bring the light-squared bishop to c4 or b5, reaching Grand Prix positions. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7
{ I believe White is slightly better after  5...g6  6.Bxc6  bxc6  d3+= } 6. O-O
e6 7. d3 a6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Qe1
{ The mainline by far. White intends to transfer the queen to the kingside.   9.e5  Ng4  transposes. }
9... Be7 10. Qg3 { White attacks the g7-pawn. } 10... O-O 11. e5 Ne8
{ As you can see, Black never takes on e5.   That would be a serious mistake since it opens the f-file for White, and allows the c1-bishop to come to h6 or g5. }
12. Be3
{ 12.Ne4?!  Happened in Sosa Rodriguez, D - Gonzalez Moreno, J 1-0 Tenerife 2017 and Black can strongly reply with  12...c4  using the fact that the e4-knight is hanging.  Black will take on d3 and use the c-file.   Meanwhile, it is not easy for White to make any progress on the kingside.  Was seen in Stojanovski,S @@StartBracket@@1989@@EndBracket@@-Kollari,S 0-1 Skopje 2013 and we recommend playing }
12... b5 13. Rad1 Rc8 { Black can follow up with Qc7-Qb7. } *

