[Black "2.Nc3 Nf6 3.f4 e5 4.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi all!   Hope you recharged your batteries for this new chapter!   In this case, we cover the lines where white starts with  2.f4  or  2.Nc3  .  Sometimes it leads to positions that have many similarities with the King's Gambit, Vienna Gambit or even closed Sicilians. }
1... d6 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4
{ I have faced this line several times, including a game against Armenian GM Andriasian.   This is an important crossroads where I will give you two different paths to follow. One of them will be the move 3...c5, transposing to a Sicilian @@StartBracket@@usually Grand Prix, which is not considered to be very dangerous@@EndBracket@@.   And the other option is the move  3...e5  , in a more Philidor style that sometimes can even transpose to King's Gambit positions. Both are deeply analyzed, so you have to choose what you prefer :@@EndBracket@@   3.Bc4  transposes to the 2.Bc4 chapter. 3.Nf3  transposes to the 2.Nf3 chapter. }
3... e5
{ There we go! This is actually the move that I have always played in my classical games. }
4. Nf3 Be7
{ We do not protect the e5 pawn! This is possible since tactics will favor Black. This position can be reached by the Vienna opening as well. }
5. fxe5 dxe5 6. Bc4
{ If White wants to play Bc4, he usually does so without taking on e5. } 6...
O-O 7. d3 Nc6 { White has employed four moves at this point. } 8. Bg5
{ was seen in Nemeckay,R @@StartBracket@@1980@@EndBracket@@-Skapikova,L  @@StartBracket@@1907@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Slovakia 2012 and I recommend you to play }
8... Bg4 9. Be3 Nd4 10. Bxd4 exd4 11. Ne2 a6
{ preparing an expansion on the queenside. } 12. Nexd4
{ 12.a3  c5  is good for Black  The text move is bad because of } 12... c5 13.
Ne2 b5 14. Bb3 c4 15. dxc4 Qb6
{ Black has managed to blow up the center and the White king is stuck in the center.   Black has a decisive advantage. }
*

