O-O 7. d3 Nc6 { White has employed four moves at this point. } 8. h3
{ 8.a3?!  This was seen in Kurpiewski, S  (2212)  (-Machul,B)  (1692)  ½-½ Mazowsze 2009, making room for the light-squared bishop but it does not stop  8...Bg4  9.Be3  Nd4  10.Bxd4  Bxf3  11.Qxf3  exd4  12.Nd5  Nd7  Black has much easier play.  Once the knight is on e5, f7 will never suffer and Black's play will be centered on the queenside, where he will advance his pawns freely. }
