{ I have faced this line several times, including a game against Armenian GM Andriasian.   This is an important crossroads where I will give you two different paths to follow. One of them will be the move 3...c5, transposing to a Sicilian @@StartBracket@@usually Grand Prix, which is not considered to be very dangerous@@EndBracket@@.   And the other option is the move  3...e5  , in a more Philidor style that sometimes can even transpose to King's Gambit positions. Both are deeply analyzed, so you have to choose what you prefer :@@EndBracket@@   3.Bc4  transposes to the 2.Bc4 chapter. 3.Nf3  transposes to the 2.Nf3 chapter. }
3... e5
{ There we go! This is actually the move that I have always played in my classical games. }
4. Nf3 Be7
{ We do not protect the e5 pawn! This is possible since tactics will favor Black. This position can be reached by the Vienna opening as well. }
5. Bc4
{ The mainline and the move that you will see in 95% of your games. People who play an early f4 love to bring the bishop to c4, which is of course a very good square targetting f7. }
5... exf4
{ We all expect White to go  6.d4  but White has other options that need to be analyzed as well. }
6. O-O Nxe4 { Is strong and has barely been played! } 7. Nxe4 d5 8. Bxd5 Qxd5
9. d3 O-O 10. Bxf4 Bf5
{ Black enjoys the bishop pair and has no weaknesses.   Worth noting that  c7  is taboo:  11.Bxc7  Bxe4  12.Bxb8  Bxf3!  or  12.dxe4  Qc5+!  and Black wins a piece! }
*

