{ In this chapter we cover 2.Nf3, which is of course a very natural move.   It is important to remark that we will analyze positions where white does not go for d4 since that would transpose to other chapters of the course. Enjoy! }
1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ White intends to play a King's Indian Attack.   There are infinite choices for black here which are completely fine. I recommend you to play }
3... g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c5
{ And we reach an important crossroads where white can try different plans. }
7. c3 Nc6 8. Re1
{ Naturally this position can be reached as well if White starts with 7.Re1 and then c3.   This is an important moment where White is threatening to play d4, that is why Black plays.   8.Nbd2  transposes to  7.Nbd2 }
8... e5 9. Na3
{ White's idea is to play Nc2 followed by d4, but Black arrives first. } 9...
h6
{ Is always a useful move covering the g5 square. Be6 will be possible without having to worry about Ng5. }
10. Nc2 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5
{ Black was slightly better in Matikozian, A @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@ -Sharavdorj,D @@StartBracket@@2411@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Burbank 2003.   This is like a revered Fianchetto King's Indian. Black is ready to continue with Be6. If white reacts in the center with }
12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 Qd6
{ The Black pieces are more active and better coordinated. } *

