{ And we reach an important crossroads where white can try different plans. }
7. c3 Nc6 8. Re1
{ Naturally this position can be reached as well if White starts with 7.Re1 and then c3.   This is an important moment where White is threatening to play d4, that is why Black plays.   8.Nbd2  transposes to  7.Nbd2 }
8... e5 9. h3
{ Prophylaxis against Bg4. White is aiming to push d4 so black should do it first!     9.d4?!  White is not ready yet to strike in the center and black is better after  9...exd4  10.cxd4  Bg4  And White cannot hold the pawn center. }
9... d5 10. exd5 Nxd5
{ And again we are in a reversed Fianchetto King's Indian.   Ideas: h6, Be6, Qc7, Re8, b6, Rb8 ,etc. }
11. Nbd2 Be6 { The natural } 12. Nc4 { Is dubious here and Black answers with }
12... f6 13. d4 { Looks strong but Black is better after } 13... Nc7
{ Covering e6 and attacking c4 and d4. } *

