{ In this chapter we cover 2.Nf3, which is of course a very natural move.   It is important to remark that we will analyze positions where white does not go for d4 since that would transpose to other chapters of the course. Enjoy! }
1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ White intends to play a King's Indian Attack.   There are infinite choices for black here which are completely fine. I recommend you to play }
3... g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c5
{ And we reach an important crossroads where white can try different plans. }
7. c3 Nc6 8. Re1
{ Naturally this position can be reached as well if White starts with 7.Re1 and then c3.   This is an important moment where White is threatening to play d4, that is why Black plays.   8.Nbd2  transposes to  7.Nbd2 }
8... e5 9. a3
{ Is a very typical idea in this position.     White wants to push b4 and force  9...a5  from Black. This way white would play  10.a4  and control the light squares on the queenside.   Instead, we play }
9... Be6 10. b4 { And this is strongly met with } 10... b5
{ I was very happy many years ago when I saw this idea for the first time in a Magnus Carlsen game.   I always used to play a5 instantaneously after White's a3 in all my games. }
11. Ng5 { 11.Nbd2  a5!=+  Once b5 is played, a5 is super strong. } 11... Bg4
12. Qc2
{ This was seen in Rubio Doblas,R @@StartBracket@@2217@@EndBracket@@-Gomez Galan Arense,J @@StartBracket@@2163@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 ICCF email 2012 and I recommend you to play }
12... h6 13. Nf3 a5 { And Black is clearly better. } *

