{ In this chapter we cover 2.Nf3, which is of course a very natural move.   It is important to remark that we will analyze positions where white does not go for d4 since that would transpose to other chapters of the course. Enjoy! }
1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ White intends to play a King's Indian Attack.   There are infinite choices for black here which are completely fine. I recommend you to play }
3... g6 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c5
{ And we reach an important crossroads where white can try different plans. }
7. Nc3
{ Is of course another playable option.   There are about 2000 games in my database, so definitely likely to see in one of your games. }
7... Nc6 8. h3 { White needs to play this move to bring the bishop to e3. }
8... Rb8 { Intending b5. } 9. a4 b6
{ And I like this secondary variation. Of course, a6 is also fine intending b5.   Black will continue with Bb7 followed by e6 if White does not try to go for d4. }
10. Be3 e5 { Black stops d4. } 11. Nd2
{ White tries to make use of the light squares. This was played in Yashas, D @@StartBracket@@2201@@EndBracket@@ -Mulay, P @@StartBracket@@1983@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Barbera del Valles 2016 and we deviate from the game with }
11... Be6 { Threatening d5. } 12. Nd5 Qd7
{ Once White does not pin the f6 knight with Bg5, Black threatens Bxd5 and Nb4 winning the d5 pawn. }
13. Bg5 Ne8
{ And Black is slightly better and ready to play f6 followed by f5. } *

