[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter we cover 2.Nf3, which is of course a very natural move.   It is important to remark that we will analyze positions where white does not go for d4 since that would transpose to other chapters of the course. Enjoy! }
1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3
{ This might seem to you a pretty weird move but it is a very interesting try.   White's idea could be to play  3...--  4.Qc2  if Black does not respond properly and then install a beautiful center after  4...--  5.d4  Naturally, if black plays  3...c5  we are transposing to an Alapin variation. No need to say that  3...Nxe4?  loses because of  Qa4+ }
3... e5 { and we analyze five different moves now. } 4. Be2 c5
{ black gains more space. } 5. O-O Be7
{ and there are some games between elite players including an Aronian vs Grischuk game. }
6. Re1 { 6.d3  transposes to the lines analyzed in 4.d3 } 6... O-O
{ Once Black has castled, e4 is actually hanging. } 7. Bc4 Nc6 8. d4
{ White is still not fully ready to strike in the center. } 8... cxd4 9. cxd4
Bg4 10. d5
{ 10.dxe5?!  was seen in Hanson,J-Karp,P  (1640)  ½-½ Natick 2003 and black should take with the pawn.  10...dxe5  and black enjoys a nice square on d4. }
10... Nd4 11. Nbd2 Qc8 { aming to take on f3. } 12. Bd3 Bd8
{ Black is slightly better after this fantastic move. The bishop finds a great diagonal on b6 and Black is more active. }
*

