{ In this chapter we cover 2.Nf3, which is of course a very natural move.   It is important to remark that we will analyze positions where white does not go for d4 since that would transpose to other chapters of the course. Enjoy! }
1. e4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Bc4
{ Whevener white goes for d4 it will transpose as you know to the main lines of this course. }
4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 Be6
{ A very solid approach, fighting already against the light squared bishop.   6...Nc6  transposes to the Italian opening. }
7. Bxe6 fxe6
{ black has doubled pawns on the e-file but at the same time, the e6 pawn does a great job covering d5 and f5. Moreover, black can create counterplay along the f-file. One important thing to note is that black wants to play c5 if allowed. }
8. Ng5
{ 8.Be3?!  allows  8...c5  and looks a bit more comfortable for Black. Nc6 and d5 seems nice.  9.Ne2  Nc6  followed by d5 }
