1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3
{ How are you guys doing?   Hope everything is fine wherever you are!   Welcome to a new chapter. In this one, we cover this move 3. f3, a very aggressive try.   White has two main ideas from this point.   The first one is to continue with  3...--  c4  what takes us to Saemisch systems and the second one is to play  3...--  Nc3  -Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O going for English attack set-ups. }
3... e5
{ This is going to be our recommendation, striking already in the center. At this crossroad, White has three main paths.   If you are a Pirc or King's Indian player, you can try  3...g6 }
4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ We already have an idea of how to play these positions after checking the endgame chapter!   There is a difference though, and this is that there is a pawn on f3 instead of a knight. The other knight on b1 is still not developed and can find other routes different from c3.   It is, of course, interesting for white but black is fine. Let's dig a bit more into the theory! }
6. Bc4 Ke8 7. Be3 { is the mainline. White covers the dark squares. } 7... a5
{ Is a novelty at this point but after a couple of moves it can transpose to positions where we start with  7...Nbd7  @@StartBracket@@which is the mainline@@EndBracket@@,  7...Nfd7  or  7...c6  . It is a very flexible move that stops from now Nh3, which is a common idea in these positions. }
8. Nc3 { d5 and b5 need to be controlled with } 8... c6 9. Nge2
{ If white allows us to expand our queenside, we should do it! } 9... b5 10.
Bd3 a4 { aiming to continue pushing with a3. } 11. a3
{ was seen in Obon Temprano,S @@StartBracket@@2160@@EndBracket@@-Mitkov,N @@StartBracket@@2552@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Sitges 2003 and we propose }
11... Na6 { With the idea of bringing the bishop to c5. } 12. O-O-O Bc5 13. Bd2
Be6
{ And we have a dreaming Philidor position!   Idea: Nd7-f6 and then Black can play Nb6-Nc4 or even Bd6-Ndc5. }
