[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3
{ How are you guys doing?   Hope everything is fine wherever you are!   Welcome to a new chapter. In this one, we cover this move 3. f3, a very aggressive try.   White has two main ideas from this point.   The first one is to continue with  3...--  c4  what takes us to Saemisch systems and the second one is to play  3...--  Nc3  -Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O going for English attack set-ups. }
3... e5
{ This is going to be our recommendation, striking already in the center. At this crossroad, White has three main paths.   If you are a Pirc or King's Indian player, you can try  3...g6 }
4. Ne2
{ Has been employed by numerous strong players.   If black plays  4...Be7  @@StartBracket@@which is the main line@@EndBracket@@ now, the idea is to proceed with  5.c4  reaching a Maroczy Bind. Instead, we strike in the center pretty fast after }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4
{ 4.Qxd4  does not make any sense, since after  4...Nc6  there is no Bb5. }
5... d5
{ Reaching very double edged positions.   One of the good news is that in practice it is very easy to go wrong for White and he has gone wrong in many tournament games. }
6. e5 { The only reasonable move at this point. } 6... Nh5
{ The best move even though  6...Nfd7  is the main line. Black is threatening Qh4 now. Out of 14 games, white went wrong in 6 now, including strong GMs. }
7. g3 { The only precise move. stopping Qh4. } 7... c5
{ The most direct attemp.   And after this move the strongest players with the white pieces went for a dubious line :@@EndBracket@@. Try to think at home what would be your next move with white.   7...g6!?  is also possible.  8.Nc3  c6  9.Bg2  Ng7  with a complex position. }
8. Nb5
{ The best move and a difficult one to make over the board. It seems dubious because one can think that after a6 white simply has to go back, but it is playable! At this point black has two options. I clearly recommend you  8...d4  leading to positions where white will have to be extremely precise, but  8...a6!?  is playable as well. We take a look at both. }
8... a6 9. Qxd5 { this is the point } 9... axb5 10. Bxb5+ Nc6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6
12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. g4 { and White traps the knight. } 13... Be7 14. gxh5 Bh4+
15. Ke2 Re8 16. Bf4 Ra4 17. Bg3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 Rxe5+ 19. Kf2 Rb4 20. b3 Rd4
{ And according to the engines this is about equal but it is not my cup of tea. Black is a pawn down but the rooks are very active and white struggles to activate the queenside. I see very few options to win with black in this kind of position. }
*

