{ the first engine suggestion, preparing Nd6+. The point is that after an eventual exd6, this will come with a check. }
9... a6 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. exd6+
{ Reaching another important crossroads where black has two decent options. I strongly recommend you to play  11...Be6  N  , which is a novelty and leads to very sharp positions where I believe white can go wrong very easily. If that day, you feel more solid you can try  11...Kf8  . Up to you! :@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Kf8 { the solid approach. } 12. Qe5 Qe8 13. Qxe8+ Kxe8
{ White has the bishop pair, but d6 is a very weak pawn. } 14. Nd2 Nc6 15. Ne4
b6 { threatening f5. } 16. g4 { is stronger. } 16... Nf6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Bh6
{ threatening Bg7 followed by Bxf6. } 18... f5 19. h3 Be6 20. Kf2 Kd7
{ d6 may fall but the bishop pair is very strong, this is why the position is about equal according to Stockfish12. }
