{ The best move even though  6...Nfd7  is the main line. Black is threatening Qh4 now. Out of 14 games, white went wrong in 6 now, including strong GMs. }
7. g3 { The only precise move. stopping Qh4. } 7... c5
{ The most direct attemp.   And after this move the strongest players with the white pieces went for a dubious line :@@EndBracket@@. Try to think at home what would be your next move with white.   7...g6!?  is also possible.  8.Nc3  c6  9.Bg2  Ng7  with a complex position. }
8. Nb5
{ The best move and a difficult one to make over the board. It seems dubious because one can think that after a6 white simply has to go back, but it is playable! At this point black has two options. I clearly recommend you  8...d4  leading to positions where white will have to be extremely precise, but  8...a6!?  is playable as well. We take a look at both. }
8... d4
{ black stops Qxd5 ideas and it is ready to kick the b5 knight. Out of three games resulting from this position, white has played three different moves. }
9. Qe2
{ the first engine suggestion, preparing Nd6+. The point is that after an eventual exd6, this will come with a check. }
9... a6 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. exd6+
{ Reaching another important crossroads where black has two decent options. I strongly recommend you to play  11...Be6  N  , which is a novelty and leads to very sharp positions where I believe white can go wrong very easily. If that day, you feel more solid you can try  11...Kf8  . Up to you! :@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Kf8 { the solid approach. } 12. Qe5 Qe8 13. Qxe8+ Kxe8
{ White has the bishop pair, but d6 is a very weak pawn. } 14. Nd2 Nc6 15. Ne4
b6 { threatening f5. } 16. Bg2
{ was seen in Galic,I @@StartBracket@@2391@@EndBracket@@ -Jovanovic,Z @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Osijek 2015 and black could have gotten a great advantage after }
16... f5 17. Nd2 Be6 { followed by Kd7, and d6 will eventually fall. } *

