1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3
{ How are you guys doing?   Hope everything is fine wherever you are!   Welcome to a new chapter. In this one, we cover this move 3. f3, a very aggressive try.   White has two main ideas from this point.   The first one is to continue with  3...--  c4  what takes us to Saemisch systems and the second one is to play  3...--  Nc3  -Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O going for English attack set-ups. }
3... e5
{ This is going to be our recommendation, striking already in the center. At this crossroad, White has three main paths.   If you are a Pirc or King's Indian player, you can try  3...g6 }
4. d5
{ Along with  4.dxe5  , the most played move. White closes the center and will reinforce it by playing c4, reaching a Saemisch-type position. In many cases, white will play Nc3-Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O, trying to start an attack on the kingside. }
4... Be7
{ The bishop on e7 is well placed. In many positions, after moving the f6-knight, Bg5 will be an appealing idea, trying to get rid off the dark squared bishops. }
5. c4
{ A very natural move. Once white has defined the pawn structure on the queenside }
5... a5 { makes a lot of sense. } 6. Nc3 Nfd7
{ A very interesting secondary line. Bg5 becomes a possibility and after Na6-Ndc5, f5 is a possible break too. }
7. Be3 Na6 { and at this point the only move played has been } 8. Qd2
{ which is the most human one, avoiding Bg5 and preparing long castle. But the good news is that it is innacurate! This is why I like this order so much with black, because many people will play like this with the white pieces. This position was seen in Nardelli,M-Scacco,M @@StartBracket@@2090@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Bratto 2003 }
8... Ndc5 { and white cannot stop f5! } 9. O-O-O
{ White threatens now g4, but it is not happening my friend!   9.g4?!  is strongly met with  Bh4!-+  if White don't want to lose his right to castle, he must play  Bf2  , after which the dark square bishop is traded, and having White played g4, it is a positional disaster.   After  9.Nge2  Black plays  h6=+  followed by Bg5, with a more comfortable position. }
9... f5 10. Kb1 O-O 11. Nge2 h6
{ and Black has a fantastic position. Bg5 is the main idea.   Even the resulting positions after closing with f4 are good for black. A sample line could be }
12. Nc1 Bg5 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Qxg5 hxg5
{ And the endgame is really great for Black.   g4 is coming very soon. Opening the f-file is an idea as well to activate the rook via f2. }
