1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3
{ How are you guys doing?   Hope everything is fine wherever you are!   Welcome to a new chapter. In this one, we cover this move 3. f3, a very aggressive try.   White has two main ideas from this point.   The first one is to continue with  3...--  c4  what takes us to Saemisch systems and the second one is to play  3...--  Nc3  -Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O going for English attack set-ups. }
3... e5
{ This is going to be our recommendation, striking already in the center. At this crossroad, White has three main paths.   If you are a Pirc or King's Indian player, you can try  3...g6 }
4. d5
{ Along with  4.dxe5  , the most played move. White closes the center and will reinforce it by playing c4, reaching a Saemisch-type position. In many cases, white will play Nc3-Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O, trying to start an attack on the kingside. }
4... Be7
{ The bishop on e7 is well placed. In many positions, after moving the f6-knight, Bg5 will be an appealing idea, trying to get rid off the dark squared bishops. }
5. Be3
{ The main line. White usually starts with this order, which is a bit more flexible than  5.c4  .  In certain positions white can proceed with Nc3.   At this point I give you two alternatives which are both interesting. }
5... O-O
{ is the main line and our second recommendation. White should be precise now with the order. }
6. Qd2
{ the second most played move and employed by several GMs, and a very natural one to the human eye. I would say it is incorrect and black can already fully equalize after concrete play. }
6... c6 7. c4 b5
{ This is the point. Black fights for the center and the d5-square. White has played three different moves now. }
8. b3
{ white protects the pawn change at any cost. This was seen in Golek,J @@StartBracket@@2026@@EndBracket@@-Leks,M @@StartBracket@@2092@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Poronin 2014. We deviate now from the game with }
8... bxc4 9. bxc4 cxd5 10. cxd5 Nh5
{ After this move, black has several ideas.   The first one is to play h6 followed by Bg5. The second one is to strike with f5 when suitable. And the last one is to jump to f4 with the knight.   Sometimes this is a very interesting pawn sacrifice, especially when white has to give up the dark squared bishop. In that case the h8-a1 diagonal gets opened and the e7-bishop can be very dangerous. }
11. Ne2 { White covers f4, so Nf4 does not make any sense now. } 11... Na6 12.
Nbc3 Rb8
{ black is slightly better. The plan is to continue with h6 followed by Bg5. }
