{ Along with  4.dxe5  , the most played move. White closes the center and will reinforce it by playing c4, reaching a Saemisch-type position. In many cases, white will play Nc3-Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O, trying to start an attack on the kingside. }
4... Be7
{ The bishop on e7 is well placed. In many positions, after moving the f6-knight, Bg5 will be an appealing idea, trying to get rid off the dark squared bishops. }
5. Be3
{ The main line. White usually starts with this order, which is a bit more flexible than  5.c4  .  In certain positions white can proceed with Nc3.   At this point I give you two alternatives which are both interesting. }
5... O-O
{ is the main line and our second recommendation. White should be precise now with the order. }
6. c4
{ The correct order. White reinforces d5 and it is now ready to continue development with Nc3, Qd2, etc. }
6... c6 7. Nc3 { 7.Qd2  transposes to the line analyzed after 6.Qd2?! } 7...
Na6
{ Deviating from the main line, which is  7...a6  . White has tried three different moves at this point. }
8. Nge2
{ White can bring the knight to g3 or even c1 in order to continue delelopment on the kingside. }
8... Bd7 9. Qd2
{ happened in Gildred,T @@StartBracket@@2427@@EndBracket@@-Rhodes,J @@StartBracket@@2429@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ ICCF email 2009. At this point }
9... h5 { is a very interesting profilactic move against g4. } 10. Nc1 cxd5 11.
cxd5 Nh7
{ This is another way of preparing Bg5. The idea is of course to play Bg5 and later f5. }
*

