{ Along with  4.dxe5  , the most played move. White closes the center and will reinforce it by playing c4, reaching a Saemisch-type position. In many cases, white will play Nc3-Be3-Qd2 and O-O-O, trying to start an attack on the kingside. }
4... Be7
{ The bishop on e7 is well placed. In many positions, after moving the f6-knight, Bg5 will be an appealing idea, trying to get rid off the dark squared bishops. }
5. Be3
{ The main line. White usually starts with this order, which is a bit more flexible than  5.c4  .  In certain positions white can proceed with Nc3.   At this point I give you two alternatives which are both interesting. }
5... c6
{ This is our first recommendation.   The idea will be to go for an early b5!? even without castling. This has barely been played and will probably surprise your opponent. It is also the first engine suggestion.   5...a5?!  does not make sense now since the c-pawn is not yet on c4. White is better after  6.Nc3+- }
6. c4 { White must reinforce the center. } 6... b5
{ This is our idea, only played in a couple of games. Black blows up white pawns chain. Naturally, black can also play  6...O-O  transposing to our second recommendation. }
7. dxc6
{ was seen in Gallagher,J @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ -Pelletier,Y @@StartBracket@@2599@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Flims 2012. We diverge from the game by playing }
7... b4
{ to cover the c3 square which is the natural one for the b1 knight, that wants to arrive to the weak square on d5. }
8. Qa4 { threatening c7+. } 8... Qc7
{ whenever white captures on b4, d5 will be coming with a lot of venom. } 9. a3
bxa3 10. Nxa3 Nxc6
{ And Black is fine.   d5 is weak but White has some weaknesses on the dark squares and is not well developed yet. }
*

