1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3
{ Welcome back everyone!   In this chapter, we cover 3.Bd3, which is the second most played move after  3.Nc3  It is a very serious move that is used often by strong GMs.   White's main idea is to reinforce the center by playing c3 and enjoy a nice center. I have faced this move on important games during my career, for example against GM Rivas or GM Bologan in the World Rapid Chess Championship in Berlin 2015.   Let's get to work! }
3... e5 { White's main response by far is } 4. d5
{ White gains some space and is aiming to continue with c4. } 4... Nbd7
{ This will be my recommendation. The idea is to play an early  Nc5  to grab the bishop pair.  4...g6!?  is another choice and may be suitable for King's Indian players. }
5. Ne2
{ A smart try. White delays c4, so Bb5+ is possible if  5...Nc5  is played. }
5... Nc5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. f3
{ And White has an edge. Black should keep the light-squared bishop in these types of positions. }
*

