1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3
{ Welcome back everyone!   In this chapter, we cover 3.Bd3, which is the second most played move after  3.Nc3  It is a very serious move that is used often by strong GMs.   White's main idea is to reinforce the center by playing c3 and enjoy a nice center. I have faced this move on important games during my career, for example against GM Rivas or GM Bologan in the World Rapid Chess Championship in Berlin 2015.   Let's get to work! }
3... e5 { White's main response by far is } 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ and I like going for the fianchetto with } 5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8.
Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 c6
{ Black prepares a possible expansion on the queenside and also the b6-square is attractive for the queen, where it puts pressure against d4 and b2. }
10. Re1 Qb6 11. Nb3 a5 12. Na4
{ 12.a4  is strongly met with  Be6=+  and white has troubles on b3 and b2. }
12... Qa7 { b5 s threatened so white is forced to play } 13. c4 Nbd7 14. Bg3
Ne5
{ With the idea of Be6. Nh5 has to be considered as well, grabbing the bishop pair. }
