1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3
{ Welcome back everyone!   In this chapter, we cover 3.Bd3, which is the second most played move after  3.Nc3  It is a very serious move that is used often by strong GMs.   White's main idea is to reinforce the center by playing c3 and enjoy a nice center. I have faced this move on important games during my career, for example against GM Rivas or GM Bologan in the World Rapid Chess Championship in Berlin 2015.   Let's get to work! }
3... e5 { White's main response by far is } 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4
{ and I like going for the fianchetto with } 5... g6 6. O-O Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8.
Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 c6
{ Black prepares a possible expansion on the queenside and also the b6-square is attractive for the queen, where it puts pressure against d4 and b2. }
10. Kh1
{ The most critical line, preparing f4. This was seen in Fuchs,G @@StartBracket@@2188@@EndBracket@@ -Walch,I @@StartBracket@@2037@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Bayern 2008. Now we recommend to play }
10... b5 11. f4 Qc7
{ The idea is the same. Black prepares the development of the b8-knight and will play a6 followed by c5. e5 needs to be very well controlled. }
12. Qf3 a6 13. Rae1 Nbd7 14. Bxf6 { white insists on playing e5. } 14... Nxf6
15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Ng4 17. Qxc6 Qxc6 18. Nxc6 Kh8
{ This is the key of this variation. Now Bd7 is coming and e5 falls. } 19. Be4
Bd7 20. h3 Rac8 21. Na7 Rc7 22. Naxb5 axb5 23. hxg4 Rc5
{ and black gets a pawn back and has fantastic compensation for the pawn thanks to the bishop pair and pressure on the c-file. The position is around equal. }
