1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3
{ Welcome back everyone!   In this chapter, we cover 3.Bd3, which is the second most played move after  3.Nc3  It is a very serious move that is used often by strong GMs.   White's main idea is to reinforce the center by playing c3 and enjoy a nice center. I have faced this move on important games during my career, for example against GM Rivas or GM Bologan in the World Rapid Chess Championship in Berlin 2015.   Let's get to work! }
3... e5 { White's main response by far is } 4. c3
{ Even though there are other interesting tries that we also analyze. } 4... d5
{ This central reaction is the main move and our recommendation. It is true that black has played d5 in two tempi but the absence of minor pieces @@StartBracket@@knights@@EndBracket@@ in the center makes this break the best move of the position. }
5. dxe5 Nxe4 6. Bxe4
{ You have no idea of how many people will go for this innacurate move!   Even many strong players have chosen this poor move.   It looks attractive, because white either wins a pawn after a check on a4, or trades queens on d8 taking the black king the right to castle, but long story short, Black will be slightly better to say the least. }
6... dxe4 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ and white must be extremely precise as we will show in order not to end up completely busted. }
8. Bg5+
{ is an interesting try, trading the dark squared bishops, but at the same time, improving the black king and helping the h-rook to come to the party. }
8... Be7 9. Bxe7+ Kxe7 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. f4
{ avoiding the black knight to come to e5 will cost white a worse pawn structure. }
11... exf3 12. Ngxf3 Be6 13. O-O-O Rad8
{ and black had a clear advantage in Spiesberger,G @@StartBracket@@2106@@EndBracket@@ -Kleissl,H @@StartBracket@@2271@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Jenbach 2009. Idea: a5, h6 and Rhe8. }
*

