1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bd3
{ Welcome back everyone!   In this chapter, we cover 3.Bd3, which is the second most played move after  3.Nc3  It is a very serious move that is used often by strong GMs.   White's main idea is to reinforce the center by playing c3 and enjoy a nice center. I have faced this move on important games during my career, for example against GM Rivas or GM Bologan in the World Rapid Chess Championship in Berlin 2015.   Let's get to work! }
3... e5 { White's main response by far is } 4. c3
{ Even though there are other interesting tries that we also analyze. } 4... d5
{ This central reaction is the main move and our recommendation. It is true that black has played d5 in two tempi but the absence of minor pieces @@StartBracket@@knights@@EndBracket@@ in the center makes this break the best move of the position. }
5. dxe5 Nxe4 6. Nf3 { The main line and the best move. } 6... Nc5
{ Black wants to capture on d3 naturally, so white bishop must be retreated. }
7. Bc2
{ The main line by far. The bishop remains in a dangerous diagonal targetting h7. }
7... Bg4 8. Bf4
{ is harmless and if white plays 'natural' moves, it can be even in danger pretty soon. }
8... Nc6 9. Nbd2 d4
{ you will see this move a lot in the rest of the chapter. These positions have some similarites with the Open Spanish Ruy López where black has this liberating move as well. }
10. O-O Be7 11. Qe1 O-O 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rd1
{ makes sense, putting the rook in front of the black queen. } 13... d3 14. Bb1
Qd5 { and Black is fine. f6 is an idea. } *

