7... Bg4 8. O-O { The main line.   8.h3  Bh5  9.O-O  transposes. } 8... Nc6
{ And at this crossroads White has tried many different moves. Black will push d4 in many cases if White does not stop it. }
9. Qe2
{ Profilaxis against d4, since Rd1 would be coming. We recommend now the novelty }
9... Ne6 { 9...Bxf3!?  N  is also playable. } 10. Rd1
{ looks like the most human move, putting pressure on d5. } 10... Qd7 11. Bb3
{ white targets the d5 pawn. Black is forced to push. } 11... d4 12. Bxe6 fxe6
13. cxd4 O-O-O
{ and again black has sacrificed a pawn for the bishop pair and pressure against d4. }
14. Nc3 Bb4
{ after this move, black is treatening to take on d4. Another plan is simply to play Rhf8 and increase pressure on f3. }
15. Bg5 { and black has two interesting choices now. } 15... Be7
{ This is our first recommendation. } 16. Be3 Rhf8 17. h3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rf5
{ and the engines say the the position is around equal. This gives an idea of how dangerous is black attack on the kingside being a pawn down. A possible way to proceed is Rdf8 followed by Qe8, transferring the queen to the kingside. }
*

