1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 Be7 5. h3
{ What are you up to?   Welcome to a new chapter. In this case, we cover 4.Nge2 followed by 5.h3.   There are only 150 games in my database with this line but it has a lot of venoms and most of the people that have used it are strong players. In this year during the pandemic, I played a lot of online tournaments including the Iberoamerican Championship.   I wanted to play the Philidor so I had a preparation match against my friend GM Miguel Santos and he came up with this idea which I found very annoying over the board. In most of the cases, White wants to continue with @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N4P/PPP1NPP1/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.g4  and start an attack already.  Ok, no more talk and let's start learning how we should react! }
5... O-O 6. g4 c6
{ This is going to be our recommendation. White has tried three moves at this point. }
7. Bg2
{ The most played move @@StartBracket@@taking always in count that there are very few games with these lines@@EndBracket@@   7.g5?!  is not a very good idea since after  Nh5!  Black blocks the attack on the kingside. }
7... Nbd7 8. a4 { The mainline, stopping b5.   8.Be3  transposes. } 8... h6
{ profilaxis against g5. } 9. O-O Re8
{ The rook is well placed on e8 and f8 can be used in the near future by the e7-bishop or even by the d7-knight as we will see. }
10. Be3 { White continues development. } 10... Nf8
{ Black is aiming to play Ng6 controlling f4 and h4. White has tried two different moves at this point. }
11. f4 { and black should be calm and play } 11... b6
{ The idea is to develop the bishop via a6 on many occasions. } 12. d5 cxd5 13.
exd5 N6d7
{ black gets ready to install a knight on e5 and to play Bg5 to trade the dark-squared bishops. }
14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 Nfg6 16. Nc6 Qd7 17. b4
{ now black has two interesting options. } 17... Bg5 18. Bxg5 hxg5
{ and the position is double-edged. Idea: Nf4. } *

