{ With this move, we are hoping that white recaptures with the knight because the position gets wild and in most cases favorable for Black. And believe me, white will go for Nxd4 in many many cases! }
7. Nxd4 d5
{ this is the whole point. Black uses the fact that white's king is still in the center to open the e-file. }
8. e5
{ This move looks annoying but in fact, white is the one that has to be extremely precise from this point. We can follow two interesting paths now }
8... c5
{ This is the move that I have employed myself in several games. It is very strong as well. It was during the preparation of this series when I discovered that engines prefer a little bit more  8...Ne8!  . Black regains the piece using the fork on d4. }
9. exf6 { 9.Ndb5  d4  10.exf6  transposes } 9... Bxf6 10. Ndb5
{ This is the other try for white. The knight jumps to b5 where in some cases is aiming to go to c7. }
10... d4 11. Bf4
{ This is an interesting try to save material for white, using the c7 square, but it fails due to }
11... dxc3 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nc7 { 13.Nxc3  Bf5-+ } 13... cxb2 14. Rb1 Nc6 15.
Nxa8 Be6
{ and Black takes on a2, getting back a whole rook and is completely winning! }
