[Black "English Attack System 4.Nge2 and 8.exd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine the 'English attack' against the Philidor.   That means a formation with a bishop on e3, a pawn on f3, and the queen on d2. White wants to castle queenside and start a pawn storm on the kingside. Black must react dynamically in the center!   I must say that I have faced this set-up in several classical games in my chess career, so it is pretty popular among white players.   And I can also tell you that I have won innumerable games with my home-analysis in this line. Many opponents will fall for the traps we have prepared.   Hope you guys can get some free points as well! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { White must start with } 4. Nge2
{ in order to go for the English attack system. White is ready to capture on d4 with the knight. }
4... Be7 5. f3
{ Prophylaxis against Ng4.   Now the bishop can be developed to e3 without troubles. }
5... O-O 6. Be3
{ And here we are going to suggest two paths to proceed.  6...c6  is the first suggestion from Stockfish and  6...exd4  is a line where white can fall in many tricks and the one that I have employed myself in all my games so far. }
6... exd4
{ With this move, we are hoping that white recaptures with the knight because the position gets wild and in most cases favorable for Black. And believe me, white will go for Nxd4 in many many cases! }
7. Nxd4 d5
{ this is the whole point. Black uses the fact that white's king is still in the center to open the e-file. }
8. exd5 Bb4
{ There is no hurry to capture the d5 pawn. We open the e-file for the rook which could be very annoying for white given that the king is still stuck in the center. }
9. Bc4 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Re8 11. Kf2 Nxd5
{ Black was slightly better because of the pawn structure in Sanchez Saez,F @@StartBracket@@2304@@EndBracket@@ -Cuenca Jimenez,J @@StartBracket@@2479@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 24th Roquetas Open 2013 }
*

