1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 Be7 5. g3
{ Welcome to this new chapter!   We analyze this set-up where white develops a knight to e2 and goes for the fianchetto. In the long term, White wants to start an attack on the kingside with f4. Black will try a queenside expansion as usual and if this is stopped by white, will try to blow up the center.   I have faced this system in 5 classical games in my chess career and many rapid games, so it is pretty common among white players. One of those games was against chess living legend Julio Granda, Grandmaster from Peru. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 c6
{ Here we go! Black intends to go b5 next move. As you can see, in this set-up is not needed Nbd7 yet, since there is no pressure on e5. }
7. O-O { if White allows us to go for b5, we should. } 7... b5
{ Sometimes I have played  7...a5  as a trick to transpose to the mainline, because we are now inviting white to play  8.a4  . But in fact 7...b5 is just a better move, so we should not be lazy @@StartBracket@@including myself of course@@EndBracket@@ and we should study this variation with 7... b5 :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. a4
{ I faced this move in an online rapid game but black is a bit better after }
8... b4 9. Nb1 a5 10. c4 bxc3 11. Nbxc3
{ fingon @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@-josecuenca @@StartBracket@@2664@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com 2016 and now }
11... Na6
{ and black's idea is to bring a knight to b4. After this, moves like Re8, Qc7, and Ba6 look attractive. }
*

