[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Philidor System with 4.Nge2 and 5.g3"]
[Black "System with 4.Nge2, 5.g3 and 7.a4 #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nge2 Be7 5. g3
{ Welcome to this new chapter!   We analyze this set-up where white develops a knight to e2 and goes for the fianchetto. In the long term, White wants to start an attack on the kingside with f4. Black will try a queenside expansion as usual and if this is stopped by white, will try to blow up the center.   I have faced this system in 5 classical games in my chess career and many rapid games, so it is pretty common among white players. One of those games was against chess living legend Julio Granda, Grandmaster from Peru. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 c6
{ Here we go! Black intends to go b5 next move. As you can see, in this set-up is not needed Nbd7 yet, since there is no pressure on e5. }
7. a4
{ The most logical move and the one that you will have to face in 90% of the games in this variation.   White stops Black's expansion. This leaves the b4 square available for our b8 knight. This is one of the advantages of not having developed the knight to d7. }
7... a5 { fixing the structure and guaranteeing the b4 square for the knight. }
8. O-O Na6 9. h3 Nb4
{ the knight not only targets c2 but also supports the d5 break. } 10. Kh2
{ improving the position of White's king. It has been played in two games according to my database. }
10... Re8 11. Be3 { and now we propose the novelty } 11... exd4
{ typical reaction in the center } 12. Nxd4 d5 13. e5
{ 13.exd5?  Nfxd5=+  comes with a tempo hitting the bishop on e3. } 13... Nd7
{ forcing } 14. e6 { If  14.f4  ,  c5!  just wins a piece. } 14... Ne5 15.
exf7+ Nxf7 16. Nce2 { c5 was a threat } 16... Na6
{ with a balanced position. Ideas: Bd6, Bd7, Qc7 or Qf6. } *

