{ Here we go! Black intends to go b5 next move. As you can see, in this set-up is not needed Nbd7 yet, since there is no pressure on e5. }
7. a4
{ The most logical move and the one that you will have to face in 90% of the games in this variation.   White stops Black's expansion. This leaves the b4 square available for our b8 knight. This is one of the advantages of not having developed the knight to d7. }
7... a5 { fixing the structure and guaranteeing the b4 square for the knight. }
8. O-O Na6 9. h3 Nb4
{ the knight not only targets c2 but also supports the d5 break. } 10. Be3
{ and from this point we advocate two approaches. } 10... d5 11. dxe5 Nxe4
{ it will never be easy for white to capture a pawn on e4 because h3 is hanging as well. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxd8 Bxd8
{ This is the key! Black leaves the e-file open to put pressure with a rook on e8. }
14. Bxe4 Re8 15. Bd4 Bxh3 16. Rfe1 f5 17. Bd3 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Bg4
{ equal according to the engines, but a very attractive position to play. } *

