1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+
{ We devote a whole chapter to study the Philidor endgame.   It is not the most critical line that white can try against the Philidor, and some people tend to think that the position is very drawish, but I think this is far from true.   The position is very interesting and both sides can play for the win. Usually, Philidor players feel comfortable with the endgame.   I have played myself this endgame in 16 classical games and only got two draws!.   Usually, these games tend to be very long, and we have to be ready to fight!   But that is what we are here for!   Last but not least, for this particular chapter, I strongly recommend you to check the analyzed games in the last part of this series so you see how to play and 'feel' these positions after studying the theory. }
5... Kxd8 6. Bg5
{ Probably the most natural move in this position. White pins the knight and is ready to castle long winning another tempo. Now we propose two ways to play. }
6... Be7
{ I have employed this move myself in many many games. It is not played as often as  6...Be6  but definetively very interesting. }
7. O-O-O+ { We can reach the same position with this order too } 7... Nbd7 8.
Bc4 Rf8 9. Nf3 Ne8 { simplifying. } *

