1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Qf3
{ We devote this chapter to study this interesting secondary line.   There are only about 150 games in the database, but it is a line that has been recommended by Spanish Super Grandmaster Paco Vallejo in his chess24 video series, so we need to take it very seriously.   Usually, it is a good weapon and surprises black players, but this will not be the case for us, since we will be very well prepared against it. White's idea is to play 7.Nf5 no matter what and grab the bishop pair.   We cannot prevent that but to do so White has to lose time with the queen and the knight which gives Black a lead in development and active counterplay. }
6... O-O 7. Nf5 Bxf5
{ We rather give up the light-squared bishop than the dark-squared one. } 8.
Qxf5 c6
{ This is going to be our idea. c6 not only supports d5 but also prepares a queenside expansion with b5. }
9. Be3
{ This is the most aggressive line. Black is well prepared to start an attack on the queenside. }
9... Nbd7 10. g4
{ This novelty is a very direct approach and the first recommendation from Stockfish12 after a short thought. It has never been played but is great to be prepared against it just in case our opponent arrives with home preparation :@@EndBracket@@ White goes all-in on the kingside without having castled. The idea is to push g5 sending the knight to a bad square. }
10... g6 11. Qf4 { 11.Qf3?  runs into  Ne5  and g4 falls. } 11... d5
{ This is a rule of thumb. Whenever our opponent starts an attack on a flank without being castled, it is usually a good idea to strike in the center. }
12. Bg2 Bb4 { Black activates the bishop putting pressure on c3. } 13. exd5
Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 cxd5
{ And we reach this strange and unclear-looking position where White has a good bishop that can land on d4 but White's pawn structure is terrible.   I would say both sides have chances.   Black has defensive ideas with f6 in case of need.   Plan: Qa5-Re8-Nb6-Re6. }
*

