1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Qf3
{ We devote this chapter to study this interesting secondary line.   There are only about 150 games in the database, but it is a line that has been recommended by Spanish Super Grandmaster Paco Vallejo in his chess24 video series, so we need to take it very seriously.   Usually, it is a good weapon and surprises black players, but this will not be the case for us, since we will be very well prepared against it. White's idea is to play 7.Nf5 no matter what and grab the bishop pair.   We cannot prevent that but to do so White has to lose time with the queen and the knight which gives Black a lead in development and active counterplay. }
6... O-O 7. Nf5 Bxf5
{ We rather give up the light-squared bishop than the dark-squared one. } 8.
Qxf5 c6
{ This is going to be our idea. c6 not only supports d5 but also prepares a queenside expansion with b5. }
9. Be3
{ This is the most aggressive line. Black is well prepared to start an attack on the queenside. }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O b5
{ Starting our attack on the queenside. At this point, only three games have been played and in the three of them   11.f3  was the move, which is probably a slight inaccuracy but the most natural move, so hopefully, your opponents will go for this option. :@@EndBracket@@  The engines find other dangerous novelties that we analyze as well. }
11. h4
{ This is a very strong novelty from Stockfish 12. White has two ideas. The first one is to push g4, and the second and most important is to free the h3 square for the queen in case it is kicked back from f5.   From h3, and having played h4, White could continue pushing all the infantry. }
11... h5
{ This move is a must.   Black should stop g4 now. Now White would try to play g4. He has two different ways to do it. }
12. f3 { White prepares g4. } 12... Re8
{ Black cannot stop g4 so we improve one piece. } 13. g4 b4 14. Nb1 g6
{ Pushing back the queen and reinforcing h5. } 15. Qf4 Qa5
{ Black also wants to party, so starts a counter-attack targetting e2 and also putting an eye on the h5 square. }
16. g5 Nh7 17. Bc4
{ f7 is weak, so bringing the bishop to this diagonal makes a lot of sense. }
17... Ne5 18. Bb3 Nf8 { The knight on h7 needs to get back to life. } 19. Qg3
{ Threatening f4 and it looks as if White is much better because of the bishop pair, but this whole line works for Black because of the next bomb: }
19... d5 { Tactics favor Black. } 20. Qxe5 { runs into } 20... Bc5 21. Qf4 Ne6
{ And White cannot protect e3. } *

