1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. g3
{ Welcome back!   In this chapter, we analyze one of the most trendy lines in the Philidor with 4...exd4.   As you already know, 2020 has been an explosion for online chess and there have been many online super tournaments. The Magnus tour and the Champions Chess Tour have gathered the best chess players in the World competing almost every month.   In these tournaments, we have seen the World Champion Magnus Carlsen and his friend Daniil Dubov playing our beloved Philidor defense with success. In those games, 6.g3 was one of the main weapons employed by the white players.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O Bf8 { and white has several choices at this point. }
9. b3 { white goes for the double fianchetto. } 9... Na6 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. Re1 c6
{ In 99% of occasions, c6 will be played. It supports a possible b5 or d5 in the future and leaves the c7 square vacant for the queen. }
12. Qd2 a5
{ gaining some space on the queenside. a4 could be an idea as well. White has employed four different moves now. }
13. a3
{ This is a prophylactic move against a4 since white can answer with b4, but I think is not very precise because black will start a pawn expansion on the queenside and after b5-a5, b4 will be threatened to put pressure on e4. }
13... Bd7 { c6 needs to be protected before pushing b5. } 14. Rad1 Qc7 15. h3
b5 { and white must stop b4 by playing } 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 Na6 18. Na2 Nc5
19. bxc5 Rxa2 20. cxd6 Qxd6
{ and black is fine and very active on the seventh rank. } *

