6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O Bf8 { and white has several choices at this point. }
9. b3 { white goes for the double fianchetto. } 9... Na6 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. Re1 c6
{ In 99% of occasions, c6 will be played. It supports a possible b5 or d5 in the future and leaves the c7 square vacant for the queen. }
12. Qd2 a5
{ gaining some space on the queenside. a4 could be an idea as well. White has employed four different moves now. }
13. Rad1
{ and among other games, this was seen in Leupold, V @@StartBracket@@2567@@EndBracket@@-Pligin, S @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ ICCF email 2009 and here we suggest to continue with }
13... Bg4 { to provoke } 14. f3 Bd7 { black threatens b5 now. } 15. a4 h6 16.
Kh1 Rc8
{ The rook looks weird on this square but it is well placed since black can open the position up with d5, and this way the c-file could get opened. The position is around equal according to the engines. Black remains solid waiting for a good opportunity. }
17. h3 Qc7 18. f4 { and the opportunity has arrived! } 18... d5 19. exd5 cxd5
20. Ndb5 Qb6
{ black gets ready to play Bf5 targetting c2. Finally, we see the point of having played Rc8 before! }
21. Nxd5 { is a serious mistake due to } 21... Nxd5 22. Qxd5 Qg6
{ and Black has a decisive advantage. g3 and c2 are under attack. Bc6 is always a dangerous idea as well. }
*

