9. b3 { white goes for the double fianchetto. } 9... Na6 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. Re1 c6
{ In 99% of occasions, c6 will be played. It supports a possible b5 or d5 in the future and leaves the c7 square vacant for the queen. }
12. Qd2 a5
{ gaining some space on the queenside. a4 could be an idea as well. White has employed four different moves now. }
13. a4
{ Fixing the structure and stopping a4.   13.h3  Qc7  14.a4  Bd7  transposes to 13.a4. }
13... Bd7 14. h3 Qc7 { and white has tried three moves at this crossroads. }
15. Re3
{ with the idea of doubling rooks on the e-file and pushing f4, was seen in Olszewski,M @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@-Schulz,K @@StartBracket@@2293@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Katowice 2017. Now we suggest the novelty }
15... Re7 { We will fight on the e-file! } 16. Rae1 Rae8 17. f4 b6 18. g4 h6
{ and the position is very complex. Black remains very solid. It is not easy for white to make progress. e5 is well controlled and f5 is a positional mistake. Idea: g6 followed by Bg7. }
