1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. g3
{ Welcome back!   In this chapter, we analyze one of the most trendy lines in the Philidor with 4...exd4.   As you already know, 2020 has been an explosion for online chess and there have been many online super tournaments. The Magnus tour and the Champions Chess Tour have gathered the best chess players in the World competing almost every month.   In these tournaments, we have seen the World Champion Magnus Carlsen and his friend Daniil Dubov playing our beloved Philidor defense with success. In those games, 6.g3 was one of the main weapons employed by the white players.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O Bf8 { and white has several choices at this point. }
9. b3 { white goes for the double fianchetto. } 9... Na6 10. Bb2 Nc5 11. Re1 c6
{ In 99% of occasions, c6 will be played. It supports a possible b5 or d5 in the future and leaves the c7 square vacant for the queen. }
12. Qd2 a5
{ gaining some space on the queenside. a4 could be an idea as well. White has employed four different moves now. }
13. a4
{ Fixing the structure and stopping a4.   13.h3  Qc7  14.a4  Bd7  transposes to 13.a4. }
13... Bd7 14. h3 Qc7 { and white has tried three moves at this crossroads. }
15. g4
{ This is always an alternative to consider in every position once white has played h3. }
15... h6 { Prophylaxis } 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. Nf5
{ This novelty seems very natural. White aims to play Qf4 and put tremendous pressure against d6. Black must play precisely from here. }
17... d5 18. exd5 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Bxf5 20. gxf5 Re8
{ Black needs the e5 square for the queen in order to target the f5 pawn. } 21.
Qd2 Qe5 22. dxc6 bxc6 23. Bxc6 Rc8 24. Bg2 Qxf5
{ And we have reached this position that the engines evaluate as equality with high depth. I recommend you to play at home with the computer to understand it better.   Black's compensation is of course based on an unsafe white king. Whenever the c3-knight is moved, the e4 square can be occupied by a black knight. Ne6-Nf4 is a strong manoeuvre as well.   A sample line given by the engines is }
25. Rc1
{ With this weird move, white protects the c2 pawn and this way the white knight can be moved without having to worry about the pawn. }
25... Ne6 26. Nd5 Nxd5 27. Qxd5 Qf4 { Bd6 or Bc5 is in the air. } 28. Qxa5 Bc5
29. Qe1 Rd8 { and Rd2 is coming! } 30. b4 Ba7 31. a5 Rd2 32. Kh1 Bb8
{ 32...Qxb4  is also possible. } 33. Kg1 Ba7 { reaching a repetition! } *

