{ Welcome back!   In this chapter, we analyze one of the most trendy lines in the Philidor with 4...exd4.   As you already know, 2020 has been an explosion for online chess and there have been many online super tournaments. The Magnus tour and the Champions Chess Tour have gathered the best chess players in the World competing almost every month.   In these tournaments, we have seen the World Champion Magnus Carlsen and his friend Daniil Dubov playing our beloved Philidor defense with success. In those games, 6.g3 was one of the main weapons employed by the white players.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O Bf8 { and white has several choices at this point. }
9. Bf4
{ White develops the bishop to a very natural square and gets ready to play Qd2 connecting the rooks. }
9... c6 10. h3 Nbd7 11. g4
{ 11.Re1  or  11.Qd2  are covered already in different order. } 11... g6
{ Again, this is a useful move making the h5 square available for the knight if White goes g5. }
12. Bg3
{ the first engine recommendation and a very natural move since f4 is an attractive idea. }
12... Qb6 13. Nb3 { is strongly met with } 13... h5 14. g5
{ and Black has a nice resource that you might have seen already in this or another chapter. }
14... h4 15. Bxh4 Nh5
{ and black has fantastic counterplay thanks to the f4 square. } 16. Kh1
{ 16.Qd2?  is terrible due to  Ne5!-+  and there are so many threats including Bxf3 followed by Nf3+ or Bg7 followed by Nc4. }
16... Ne5
{ aiming for the c4 square. Nf4 is also strong now once white cannot play Qg4. }
17. f4 Nc4 18. Bf2 Qc7 19. Qf3 Nxb2
{ with an equal and double edged position. The knight is coming back home via c4. Whenever white pushes f5, black will enjoy a great knight on e5. }
