9. Bf4
{ White develops the bishop to a very natural square and gets ready to play Qd2 connecting the rooks. }
9... c6 10. Qd2 Nbd7 { and White has tried four moves at this crossroads. } 11.
h3 Ne5 12. Rad1 b5 13. b3
{ 13.Bxe5?  dxe5  14.Nxc6  Qb6-+  and the knight is trapped. } 13... b4 14. Na4
c5 15. Nb5
{ This was seen in Vachier Lagrave, M @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@-Rapport,R @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Biel 2015.   As an anecdote, I analyzed this position in 2017 with a much less powerful engine, and the evaluation it showed was decisive advantage for White. Newer engines show that this position is completely balanced.   Black must play the novelty }
15... Ba6 16. Nxd6 Bxd6 17. Qxd6 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Qa5
{ Threatening Rad8, and forcing white to play } 19. Qxc5 Qa6+ 20. Kg1 Qe2
{ Black activates the queen and targets c2, e4 and it also intends Nf3+. White's only move to equalize is }
21. Qd4 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Qxf3 23. e5 Nh5
{ and once more the only move for white is } 24. Rd3 Nxf4 25. gxf4 Qe2
{ with equality even though white is the one that needs to be extremely careful since the white king is very exposed. }
