1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. g3
{ Welcome back!   In this chapter, we analyze one of the most trendy lines in the Philidor with 4...exd4.   As you already know, 2020 has been an explosion for online chess and there have been many online super tournaments. The Magnus tour and the Champions Chess Tour have gathered the best chess players in the World competing almost every month.   In these tournaments, we have seen the World Champion Magnus Carlsen and his friend Daniil Dubov playing our beloved Philidor defense with success. In those games, 6.g3 was one of the main weapons employed by the white players.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 Re8 8. O-O Bf8 { and white has several choices at this point. }
9. h3
{ The mainline. White prepares g4, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.   9.Re1  c6  10.h3  transposes to 9.h3   9.Bg5?!  h6  10.Bf4  is a favorable version for black of the lines with 9.Bf4 since h6 is part of the plan anyway. }
9... Nbd7 10. g4
{ The most critical variation. It is very trendy nowadays since Karjakin played it against Carlsen in the Magnus Tour.   10.b3  Nc5  11.Re1  transposes to 9.b3 }
10... Nc5 11. Re1 c6 { and white has played four moves here. } 12. Bf4
{ a very logical move, simply going after the weakness on d6. } 12... Ne6 13.
Bg3 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 h5 15. g5 Nd7 { g5 must be protected now. } 16. f4
{ the most critical line. White stops Ne5. } 16... Qb6
{ black must go for the endgame. } 17. Qxb6 axb6
{ At first glance, the engines thought white was better so I had to tune up the analysis. Black holds. Black is intending to push b5 so white best move is }
18. a4 Nc5 19. Bf2 g6 { and white's only move to put pressure is } 20. Red1 h4
{ a great pawn sacrifice that the engine does not understand at the beginning! Black deflects the bishop from the g1-a7 diagonal so the b6 pawn does not suffer after moving the knight in the following lines. }
21. Bxh4 Bg7 22. Rxd6 Bxc3 23. bxc3 Nxe4 { straight away does not work due to }
24. Bxe4 Rxe4 25. Rd8+ Kg7 26. Re1 Rxe1+ 27. Bxe1
{ and the bishop will be sooner or later in the main diagonal creating nasty mating threats against the black king. }
*

