[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze in deep the sharpest line of the Philidor with 4...exd4.   White will play 6.Bf4 to follow with Qd2 and O-O-O. To be completely honest with you, this chapter has given me a constant headache for a couple of weeks.   Wesley So, in his e4 Lifetime Repertoires series for Chessable, dedicates five chapters to the Philidor. His analysis of course is world-class and his preparation is amazing. He actually recommends 6.Bf4. The lines he shows against our beloved defense are great and I have been several nights trying to find the best way to deal with it.  After more than 30 hours of research, I found a line that in my opinion equalizes. This is probably one of the most important chapters from the theoretical point of view, and supercomputers are needed to refine the lines until the end.   This means these lines are tested with depth at least 45-50 in Stockfish 12.   Lines are exciting and hard to understand, but as usual in turbulent waters, if we come to the game with the home analysis learned, it will be our opponent the one who will struggle to find the right moves.   Fasten your seatbelts because some curves are coming! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... d5
{ Striking in the center already. This move has been played by several strong Grandmasters and leads to huge complications. It is a good surprising weapon.   When I was preparing this series, my first intention was to recommend  7...c6  , a very aggressive move employed by non-other than Magnus Carlsen in 2020 against Leinier Domínguez, but I could not fully equalize after  8.O-O-O  b5  9.f3  b4  10.Na4! }
8. Ndb5
{ The mainline by far. 204 games in my database while only less than 30 with  8.e5  and  8.O-O-O  . White targets c7 and the d5 pawn. }
8... Bb4 { and the party starts. } 9. O-O-O { the mainline by far. } 9... c6
10. Nc7
{ This is all forced. We have to be ready to sacrifice a rook. Who dares to say that the Philidor is boring? Let's party! }
10... Nxe4
{ And now White has two possibilities and both have been played more or less the same. Black is using all it can against the white king. We have to take in count that our a8 rook is completely lost. }
11. Qd4 { the best move and So's recommendation. } 11... Nxc3
{ This will be our approach.   It has been played only in 6 games so we will have decent chances to surprise our opponents. The lines as usual are completely insane.   If our opponent finds all precise moves, black will have to defend a slightly worse position, as pointed out by Wesley So in his e4 lifetime repertoire video series.   This is why 7... d5?! is not our main recommendation. But anyway, I think it is a good surprising weapon and White has many different ways to go wrong.   11...Nxc3  is the mainline. I was tempted to show you as well, the theory behind that move but I think this chapter is already too thick. }
12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Bg4 { is a novelty and the best move by far. } 14. f3 Be6
15. Nxa8 Qa5
{ Black has several dangerous ideas including c5 followed by c4 or d4. } 16.
Bd2
{ The best move and the only one where White fights for advantage. Prophylaxis against c5. }
16... Na6 { 16...c5?  is not good now because of  c4!  and Black can resign. }
17. c4 Bb4 18. cxd5 { We follow as mainline So's recommendation. } 18... Bxd5
19. Bxb4 Nxb4 20. Bc4 { and here we propose } 20... b5
{ Wesley So analyzes  20...Bxc4 } 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 22. Kb2 Rxa8
{ And we reach this position where Black has a knight and a pawn for the rook. The engines think this is better for White @@StartBracket@@0.60-0.80@@EndBracket@@.   Even so, it is tough for White to make progress and White should always pay attention to his king which is not going to be completely safe.   I recommend 20...b5 because Black can play b4, to prevent White from consolidating with c3. }
23. Rhe1 { 23.c3  runs into  b4!-+ } 23... b4 24. Qc4 h6
{ This is the risk we take when going for this line and the reason why my recommendation is 7...Nc6.   If we play this variation, we will have to live with this possibility and black cannot fully equalize, but as I told you, still a very complicated position. }
*

