1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... Nc6
{ In these variations, the kings will be on opposite flanks. The game will continue as an exciting race and as usual, the one arriving first wins! }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. Qd2 { Prophylaxis against c5. } 11... b5 12. g4
{ Now c5 does not gain any tempo so we are going to propose a very interesting pawn sacrifice! Besides, it is a novelty :@@EndBracket@@ }
12... c6
{ Black's idea is to push with d5.   If White does accept the challenge and takes the d6-pawn, Black will have tremendous play as shown in the following analysis. }
13. Bxd6 Bxd6 14. Qxd6 Qa5
{ This is the point. Black threatens b4 by followed by Qxa2. Whenever White plays a3, b4 will come with more damage. }
15. a3 Rfd8 { and now there is an only move for White to fight for equality, }
16. Qg3
{ Is a mistake. In the next variations I will show you the only optimal response of White.   White's queen should keep an eye on the b4 square because now }
16... b4 { opening lines is just too strong. } 17. Nb1 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1
{ look at that king! } 18... bxa3 19. Nxa3 Qb6 20. b3 a5
{ with the simple threat of blowing up the position with a4 is winning for Black. }
*

