1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze in deep the sharpest line of the Philidor with 4...exd4.   White will play 6.Bf4 to follow with Qd2 and O-O-O. To be completely honest with you, this chapter has given me a constant headache for a couple of weeks.   Wesley So, in his e4 Lifetime Repertoires series for Chessable, dedicates five chapters to the Philidor. His analysis of course is world-class and his preparation is amazing. He actually recommends 6.Bf4. The lines he shows against our beloved defense are great and I have been several nights trying to find the best way to deal with it.  After more than 30 hours of research, I found a line that in my opinion equalizes. This is probably one of the most important chapters from the theoretical point of view, and supercomputers are needed to refine the lines until the end.   This means these lines are tested with depth at least 45-50 in Stockfish 12.   Lines are exciting and hard to understand, but as usual in turbulent waters, if we come to the game with the home analysis learned, it will be our opponent the one who will struggle to find the right moves.   Fasten your seatbelts because some curves are coming! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... Nc6
{ In these variations, the kings will be on opposite flanks. The game will continue as an exciting race and as usual, the one arriving first wins! }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. Kb1 { a very common move bringing the king to a safer square. } 12... c6
{ This idea has been played only once and again is super interesting.   12...c5  is the mainline. }
13. Be2 { a slow move that allows black to continue attacking with } 13... Qa5
14. b3 d5 15. g5 Bb4 { forcing White to go } 16. Bc7 Qxc7 17. Qxb4 Nh5 18. exd5
cxd5 { with a fine position for Black. White cannot take on d5. If } 19. Nxd5
{ then } 19... Bxd5 20. Rxd5 Nf4 21. Rd2 Qe5
{ taking on g5 next and the knight is better than the bishop. } *

