10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. h4 { The critical line! } 12... c5 13. Qd2
{ The mainline by far. The lines shown will be crazy and very complicated. }
13... b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bd7
{ And we reach this interesting position.   White will try to push h5-g5 and then decide what to do. Sometimes a bishop on d3 can be dangerous as well.   On the other side of the board, Black will push the a-pawn until a3, to create some mating ideas on b2.   Wesley So said he is not sure if White can get an advantage.   I would say it is a fun position to play with chances for both sides!   Let's dig a little bit!   White has three decent alternatives now: pushing the pawns or improving the king. }
16. Kb1 a5 17. h5
{ The most direct approach.   17.g5  Bf5  18.Bd3  transposes } 17... a4
{ Fasten your seat belts: crazy lines are coming.   Take your medicine before checking this! }
18. Bd3
{ Targetting h7 and preparing the rook lift to g1 in many cases.   Moreover, White can continue with g5 and there will be no Bf5 from Black. }
18... h6
{ This move is needed now. The idea of course is to play Bg5. The sacrifice on h6 is very very dangerous but Black holds! }
19. Bxh6 { Black cannot take. It looks winning but there is a nice resource! }
19... c4 { Black tries to deflect the bishop from the focal point on h7. } 20.
Be4 c3 { more deflection! } 21. Qe3 { the only good move for White. } 21... b3
{ fantastic entropy in this position. Nice term for those who like physics. We have to analyze many different options including all possible captures :@@EndBracket@@ The good news is that White has so many ways to go wrong! }
22. bxc3 Rc8 23. Bf4
{ White has to retreat the bishop at some point to continue the attack but Black strikes first.   23.Rd3  is the best try for White  Re8  with an unclear position. Idea: Bb5 }
23... f5 24. gxf5 { 24.Bxf5?  runs into  Rxf5! } 24... Bf6
{ This way the e4-bishop does not contribute on the kingside and the f6-bishop not only covers g7 but targets c3. }
25. cxb3 axb3 26. a3 Rxc3 27. Rd3 Rxd3 28. Qxd3 Qb6 29. h6 Ra8 30. Bc1 Ra5
{ The key move of the whole variation. Black threatens b2 now! } 31. Rd1 Qc5
{ Followed by Rxa3 with a decisive attack. } *

