[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. b) Philidor 6.Bf4"]
[Black "Philidor 6.Bf4, 8.O-O-O and 9.Qxd4 #44"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze in deep the sharpest line of the Philidor with 4...exd4.   White will play 6.Bf4 to follow with Qd2 and O-O-O. To be completely honest with you, this chapter has given me a constant headache for a couple of weeks.   Wesley so, in his e4 Lifetime Repertoires series for Chessable, dedicates five chapters to the Philidor. His analysis of course is world-class and his preparation is amazing. He actually recommends 6.Bf4. The lines he shows against our beloved defense are great and I have been several nights trying to find the best way to deal with it.  After more than 30 hours of research, I found a line that in my opinion equalizes. This is probably one of the most important chapters from the theoretical point of view, and supercomputers are needed to refine the lines until the end.   This means these lines are tested with depth at least 45-50 in Stockfish 12.   Lines are exciting and hard to understand, but as usual in turbulent waters, if we come to the game with the home analysis learned, it will be our opponent the one who will struggle to find the right moves.   Fasten your seatbelts because some curves are coming! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... Nc6
{ In these variations, the kings will be in opposite flanks. The game will continue as an exciting race and as usual, the one arriving first wins! }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. h4 { The critical line! } 12... c5 13. Qd2
{ The mainline by far. The lines shown will be crazy and very complicated. }
13... b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bd7
{ And we reach this interesting position.   White will try to push h5-g5 and then decide what to do. Sometimes a bishop on d3 can be dangerous as well.   On the other side of the board, Black will push the a-pawn until a3, to create some mating ideas on b2.   Wesley So said he is not sure if White can get an advantage.   I would say it is a fun position to play with chances for both sides!   Let's dig a little bit!   White has three decent alternatives now: pushing the pawns or improving the king. }
16. g5 { The most played move and perhaps the most natural. } 16... Bf5
{ We improve our bishop. } 17. h5
{ is a novelty here but must be considered since again it looks very normal. }
17... Re8 18. Kb1 Bf8 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 g6
{ Black wants to place the bishop on g7 so that is why White plays } 21. h6 f6
22. Rhg1 a5
{ once we have stopped the attack on the kingside it is time to push our babys! }
23. Bc1 Qe7 24. gxf6 Qxf6 25. Bg5 Qf7 26. f4
{ and White is threatening f5 blowing up the kingside so } 26... Qf5
{ is needed } 27. Qxf5 gxf5 { and White has no dangerous discovered checks. }
28. Bh4+ Kf7 29. Rg5 { the f5 pawn falls but after } 29... Re4 30. Rxf5+ Ke8
{ Black is completely fine. Our plan is Ra7-Rf7 and eventually White will lose a pawn on the kingside.   The e4-rook is very active and controls the d1-rook that has to guard the backrank. }
31. Bg5 Ra7 32. c3 bxc3 33. bxc3 Rb7+ 34. Kc1 Re2
{ reaching a balanced endgame. } *

