30. c5 Ng3 31. Rhg1 { is the other option. } 31... Bd5
{ Black needs to protect the e4-pawn. } 32. h5 gxh5
{ 32...Nxh5?!  leaves the knight out of play and after  33.Bh3  White is better. }
33. Bh3 h4 34. Bxc8 Rxc8
{ And this is a super interesting position where Black is an exchange down but not worse. The h and e-pawns are very dangerous. The idea is to proceed with h6-Kh7, etc. }
35. Rd1 { looks tempting but it is not accurate because of } 35... Ne2
{ Using the fork on c3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. b) Philidor 6.Bf4"]
[Black "Philidor 6.Bf4, 7Qd2 and 9.Qxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze in deep the sharpest line of the Philidor with 4...exd4.   White will play 6.Bf4 to follow with Qd2 and O-O-O. To be completely honest with you, this chapter has given me a constant headache for a couple of weeks.   Wesley so, in his e4 Lifetime Repertoires series for Chessable, dedicates five chapters to the Philidor. His analysis of course is world-class and his preparation is amazing. He actually recommends 6.Bf4. The lines he shows against our beloved defense are great and I have been several nights trying to find the best way to deal with it.  After more than 30 hours of research, I found a line that in my opinion equalizes. This is probably one of the most important chapters from the theoretical point of view, and supercomputers are needed to refine the lines until the end.   This means these lines are tested with depth at least 45-50 in Stockfish 12.   Lines are exciting and hard to understand, but as usual in turbulent waters, if we come to the game with the home analysis learned, it will be our opponent the one who will struggle to find the right moves.   Fasten your seatbelts because some curves are coming! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2
{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... Nc6
{ In these variations, the kings will be in opposite flanks. The game will continue as an exciting race and as usual, the one arriving first wins! }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. h4 { The critical line! } 12... c5 13. Qe3
{ The best move that has been barely played. It is Wesley So's recommendations in his Chessable e4 lifetime repertoire. }
13... b4 14. Na4
{ This is white's idea. Now there is pressure on c5 and d6, and the a4-knight makes difficult the progress on the queenside. }
14... Qc7 15. b3
{ Wesley So talks about this move but ends up recommending  15.h5  . Here we analyze it deeply too.   White consolidates the queenside and gets ready to continue the party on the kingside.   We propose now two ways to proceed. }
15... Qc6
{ Black prepares a central reaction with d5 and is hoping to transpose to the studied main line after  16.h5  . }
16. g5
{ Not the usual way to push, because it allows the blockade with Nh5, but white will have f4-f5 ideas and pressure along the d-file. }
16... Nh5 17. Bh2 Rfe8 18. f4 { the most dangerous idea. } 18... Bf8
{ reminding White that there is pressure along the e-file. Bf5! is an idea. }
19. Bg2
{ Black has to be very careful along the big diagonal.   19.Nb2?  runs into  Bf5! }
19... Bg4 20. Rde1 { the most natural move protectins the e4-pawn. } 20... g6
{ Black intends Bg7-Bd4 or c4. } 21. Qf2
{ A strong precise move. White removes the queen from the dangerous e-file and protects g2, which means that e5 is already a dangerous idea.   22.Nb2?  is too slow and allows  Bg7!=+ }
21... c4 { time to attack! } 22. f5
{ White leaves the g4-bishop in a dangerous position.   22.e5?  d5! } 22...
Rad8 { and at this point, we analyze four different options. } 23. f6
{ I think this is the best option for White.   It looks strange because White gives up on the attack by closing the kingside, but White has more space. }
23... Be6 { Threatening cxb3 followed by Bxb3. Moreover, Black prepares d5. }
24. Kb1 { prophylaxis } 24... d5 25. Qb6 Qxb6 26. Nxb6 dxe4
{ And here the best move for White is } 27. bxc4
{ If  27.Nxc4  Bf5=  Black manages to protect the e4 pawn with a healthy position. }
27... Bc5 28. Bc7 Bxb6 29. Bxb6 Rc8
{ And White is slightly better. The resulting positions are crazy and very double-edged.   White has the bishop pair and a dangerous passed pawn on the c-file but Black has the e-pawn which will be a nightmare for White in many variations as shown. }
30. c5 Ng3 31. Rhg1 { is the other option. } 31... Bd5
{ Black needs to protect the e4-pawn. } 32. Bh3 Nf5
{ My supercomputer says 0.20 for white at depth 50. Black's idea is to play Re5 next.   The bishop will probably end up on c6. The e-pawn at some point will be pushed. }
*

