{ Our recommendation will be to go for the mainline with  7...Nc6  . We also examine the crazy complications that arise after  7...d5!? }
7... Nc6
{ In these variations, the kings will be in opposite flanks. The game will continue as an exciting race and as usual, the one arriving first wins! }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6
{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. h4 { The critical line! } 12... c5 13. Qe3
{ The best move that has been barely played. It is Wesley So's recommendations in his Chessable e4 lifetime repertoire. }
13... b4 14. Na4
{ This is white's idea. Now there is pressure on c5 and d6, and the a4-knight makes difficult the progress on the queenside. }
14... Qc7 15. b3
{ Wesley So talks about this move but ends up recommending  15.h5  . Here we analyze it deeply too.   White consolidates the queenside and gets ready to continue the party on the kingside.   We propose now two ways to proceed. }
15... Qc6
{ Black prepares a central reaction with d5 and is hoping to transpose to the studied main line after  16.h5  . }
16. g5
{ Not the usual way to push, because it allows the blockade with Nh5, but white will have f4-f5 ideas and pressure along the d-file. }
16... Nh5 17. Bh2 Rfe8 18. f4 { the most dangerous idea. } 18... Bf8
{ reminding White that there is pressure along the e-file. Bf5! is an idea. }
19. Bg2
{ Black has to be very careful along the big diagonal.   19.Nb2?  runs into  Bf5! }
19... Bg4 20. Rde1 { the most natural move protectins the e4-pawn. } 20... g6
{ Black intends Bg7-Bd4 or c4. } 21. Qf2
{ A strong precise move. White removes the queen from the dangerous e-file and protects g2, which means that e5 is already a dangerous idea.   22.Nb2?  is too slow and allows  Bg7!=+ }
21... c4 { time to attack! } 22. f5
{ White leaves the g4-bishop in a dangerous position.   22.e5?  d5! } 22...
Rad8 { and at this point, we analyze four different options. } 23. Rhg1
{ white wants to play Bh1 and grab the fruit on g4. Black has to apply concrete measures again. }
23... gxf5 24. exf5 Qb5 { targetting f5. Now White has two decent options. }
25. Be4 d5 { the only move since the g4 bishop is attacked. } 26. Rxg4
{ being greedy and getting the pawn means that Black is better after } 26...
dxe4 27. Rgxe4 Rxe4 28. Rxe4 c3
{ White has back rank problems and the a4-knight is completely out of play. Idea: Qd7. }
*

