{ Black develops the bishop and is ready to start pushing with a6 and b5. White will do the same on the kingside. }
10. f3
{ The mainline. White prepares for a kingside expansion with g4.   10.Kb1  a6  11.f3  transposes   10.Qd2  a6  11.f3  transposes }
10... a6 11. g4
{ White does not waste any tempo and goes all-in against our king. } 11... b5
12. h4 { The critical line! } 12... c5 13. Qe3
{ The best move that has been barely played. It is Wesley So's recommendations in his Chessable e4 lifetime repertoire. }
13... b4 14. Na4
{ This is white's idea. Now there is pressure on c5 and d6, and the a4-knight makes difficult the progress on the queenside. }
14... Qc7 15. h5
{ We keep considering Wesley's recommendation as to the mainline. White needs to push h5 first so after g5 the knight cannot land on h5. }
15... Qc6 { White attacks the a4-knight and prepares a central reaction. } 16.
b3 d5 { Black wants to push d4. } 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Qe4 Rac8 19. h6
{ This move is very important. } 19... g5
{ Black should avoid the opening of the h-file and this way it wins a tempo hitting the bishop. }
20. Be5 Nf4 { offering a queen trade that White should accept. } 21. Qxc6 Rxc6
22. Rd2
{ And here Wesley So stops his analysis concluding that White has a good advantage.   As I told you at the beginning of this course I had several bad days trying to equalize against these lines but after playing here and there with supercomputers I think I managed.   The lines are very deep and concrete and Black has to be precise but the good news is that I think Black holds.   I give you two options now and both are playable. }
22... Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Bxd8 24. Bxf4
{ this move is necessary to bring the f1-bishop to the game. } 24... gxf4
{ and at this point, we analyze four possible moves. } 25. Rh5
{ targetting c5. Black should be very careful now. } 25... f5
{ Facundo solving the issue once more!   Black sacrifices a pawn to block the rook's attack on c5. The king will arrive to f6 soon and h6 is always attacked from c6. }
26. gxf5 Bd5 27. Rh3 c4 { Black gets rid of the c5-weakness } 28. Bxc4 Bxc4 29.
bxc4 Rxc4 30. Nb2
{ finally the knight gets back to life. Black can hold. A sample line could be }
30... Rc5 31. Nd3 Rxf5 32. Nxb4 Bf6 33. Nxa6 Ra5 34. Nb4 Bc3 35. Nd3 Rxa2 36.
Kd1 Ra1+ 37. Ke2 Ra2 38. Nxf4 Be5 { After this key move Black equalizes. } 39.
Nd3 Rxc2+ 40. Ke3 Bc7
{ and White does not have enough. h6 is weak all the time and remember that Rook vs Rook+knight is still a draw! }
*

