28. Rd1
{ Perhaps the most natural move, because the rook arrives to the seventh rank. }
28... Be7 29. Rd7 Bf8 { targetting h6. White is forced to play } 30. Rd8 Rc6
{ attacking h6. } 31. g5 { and here we have to play an only move which is }
31... f5
{ The rook should cover the g6 square! The king wants to leave the back rank.   31...f6?  loses on the spot because of  g6! }
32. Nb2 Kf7 33. Nd3 Bd6 { And again the bishop controls all the knight jumps. }
34. Kd2 a5 35. Rd7+ Kg6 36. Rg7+ Kh5
{ White cannot improve his position any further so the only way forward is to take the h7 pawn. }
37. Rxh7 Kxg5 38. Rf7 Kxh6 39. Rxf5 Ra6 40. Nxf4 Bxf4+ 41. Rxf4 Rd6+
{ Reaching a rook endgame in which Black can build a fortress. } 42. Kc1 Kg5
43. Rf8 Rc6 { Followed by Rc3 and Ra3 when White cannot make any progress! }
44. Kb2 Rc3
{ I am exhausted after analyzing and understanding all these crazy variations.   I guess you guys too, but work pays off!   See you in the next chapter! }
