9. Bf1
{ Perhaps the most logical move having played Re1 in the previous one. Now my recommendation is  9...b4  but I have analyzed an interesting second option as well. }
9... Re8
{ our second option. This is always a useful move. The f8 square is available now for the bishop. Depending how white plays, we will strike in the center with d5 or will play more calm with moves like Qc7, Bf8, Nbd7,etc. }
10. a3 { Profilaxis against b4. } 10... Qc7
{ 10...Bf8?!  is innacurate. There is a fantastic trick that we should be aware of.  11.Bg5!  and  h6  is not possible because of  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.Ndxb5!  cxb5  14.Qd5!+-  and Black has to give up the piece in order to save the rook, and White  is a healthy pawn up. }
11. Bg5 a5 12. Qd2 Nbd7
{ If  12...Na6?  we just fell for another trick after  13.Nxc6! } 13. Nf5 Bf8
{ Once the a8-rook is protected, b4 would be a real threat. } 14. Bh4 Qb8
{ A good move!   Black threatens now b4 and keeps the bishop on c8, which in the future could be useful for a trade on f5. }
15. f3 b4 16. axb4 axb4 17. Rxa8 bxc3
{ nice intermediate move! and white luckily holds with } 18. Qg5 Qxa8 19. Nh6+
Kh8 20. Nxf7+ Kg8 21. Nh6+ { perpetual. } *

