{ How are you guys doing? I hope you are enjoying the series.   In this new chapter, we examine the lines with 6.Bc4.   It is the second most played move after  6.Be2  , so you will see it a lot in your games.  The a2-g8 diagonal seems a good one to place a bishop. As it usually happens in the Philidor, positions are very flexible and there are many interesting ways to play.   Moreover, there are not so many forced lines, and it is an opening that is not only learned by studying the theory but also by playing lots of games in order to 'feel' the positions.   I will recommend you to play with an early c6, intending a queenside expansion with b5 or a central reaction with d5.   Enjoy! }
6... O-O 7. O-O c6
{ Is our recommendation. We will either play b5 or d5 next move depending on white's response.   7...Re8  8.Re1  a6  is another way to play and so far pretty unexplored. }
8. Re1 { white does not stop b5, so we go for it. } 8... b5
{ 8...a5  9.a4  Na6  10.Bf4  Nc5  was seen in Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ -Dubov,D @@StartBracket@@2699@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 chess24.com INT 2020 }
9. Bf1
{ Perhaps the most logical move having played Re1 in the previous one. Now my recommendation is  9...b4  but I have analyzed an interesting second option as well. }
9... Re8
{ our second option. This is always a useful move. The f8 square is available now for the bishop. Depending how white plays, we will strike in the center with d5 or will play more calm with moves like Qc7, Bf8, Nbd7,etc. }
10. f3
{ was played in Turov,M @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@-Marin,M @@StartBracket@@2511@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 playchess.com INT 2004. We diverge from the game suggesting two novelties. Our first recommendation is the first move from Stockfish 12. It leads to strategic and calm positions. The second alternative leads to super crazy variations. You can choose! }
10... d5
{ using the fact that white has weakened its kingside with f3, there will be some tricks along the a7-g1 diagonal. Do not be afraid with the engine! You need to let it run for a while.   In fact white will need to be extremely precise and it is pretty easy to collapse with the white pieces in the following positions. Fasten your seatbelts! }
11. e5 { This is the critical test. } 11... Bc5
{ 11...Nfd7  is bad because of  12.e6! } 12. Kh1 Nh5
{ Black's threat is Qh4 followed by Ng3 mate. } 13. Be3
{ leads to a crazy forced draw! } 13... Rxe5 14. Nxc6
{ this is white's idea and looks they tricked us but.. } 14... Bxe3
{ boom! Some nice mating ideas along the h-file! } 15. Nxd8 Ng3+ 16. hxg3 Rh5#
{ Who would not love to finish one game like that? :@@EndBracket@@ } *

