1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Bc4
{ How are you guys doing? I hope you are enjoying the series.   In this new chapter, we examine the lines with 6.Bc4.   It is the second most played move after  6.Be2  , so you will see it a lot in your games.  The a2-g8 diagonal seems a good one to place a bishop. As it usually happens in the Philidor, positions are very flexible and there are many interesting ways to play.   Moreover, there are not so many forced lines, and it is an opening that is not only learned by studying the theory but also by playing lots of games in order to 'feel' the positions.   I will recommend you to play with an early c6, intending a queenside expansion with b5 or a central reaction with d5.   Enjoy! }
6... O-O 7. O-O c6
{ Is our recommendation. We will either play b5 or d5 next move depending on white's response.   7...Re8  8.Re1  a6  is another way to play and so far pretty unexplored. }
8. a4
{ The main continuation and the most logical stopping b5. Now we react in the center with the move }
8... Nxe4 { is again possible. } 9. Nxe4 d5 10. Bd3 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Bf6 12. c3
Bxd4 13. cxd4 Nd7
{ I feel this is very close to equality but still white has a slight edge and it is not my cup of tea. Too dry! }
