1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine deeply the lines where White plays 6. Be2, a very normal move that you will face in many of your games. It is actually the most played move after 5...Be7, so definitely a chapter that is worth paying attention to! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Be2
{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Re1
{ white wants to protect the e4 pawn without weakening the kingside with the move f3. At this point we suggest two different ways to play with the black pieces so you can decide which one is your cup of tea. }
8... Bf8 { The mainline by far. } 9. Bg5
{ this is probably the most dangerous try for white and it was employed by Safarli against Mamedyarov in 2019, so it deserves very serious attention. }
9... h6
{ If white does not want to give up the bishop pair, it has to be ready to sacrifice the e4-pawn. }
10. Bh4
{ 10.Bxf6?!  Qxf6  This is a dreaming position for Black.  Bishop pair and nothing in return. The black bishop can be very strong in the long term because it has no opposition. }
10... g5 11. Bg3
{ Taking the e4 pawn is very dangerous so we are proposing the novelty } 11...
Bd7
{ If  11...Nc6?!  then  12.Nxc6  bxc6  and  13.e5!  ruining Black's pawn structure with a better position for White. }
12. Bc4 { If  12.f4  now  Nxe4  is good for Black. } 12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6
14. Qd3 { makes also sense to bring the rook to the center. } 14... Bg7 15.
Rad1 Qe7 16. Re3
{ with the idea of bringing the rook to the f-file putting pressure on f7. }
16... Ng4 17. Rf3 Nf6 { the knight goes back targetting e4 as well. } 18. h4
{ 18.Re3  leads to repetition.   18.Re1  looks natural but after  Qd7  Black is fine and threatening d5.  Re7-Rae8 is also a nice idea. }
18... Bxe4 19. Nxe4 Qxe4 20. Qb3
{ White must avoid the queen trade to fight for an advantage. } 20... Re7 21.
Re3 Qg4 { Only move. The d1-rook is unprotected. } 22. Rxe7 Qxd1+ 23. Bf1 Nd5
24. Qxb7 Rf8 25. Re2 f5
{ Black reacts pretty fast on the kingside.   White should play precisely to equalize. }
26. hxg5 hxg5 27. c4 f4 28. Bh2 Nf6 29. Qxc7 Ng4
{ Threatening Nxh2.   White has only one move to equalize. } 30. Qd7 Ne3
{ 30...Nxh2?  is a blunder and white wins after  31.Re7! } 31. Qe6+
{ Reaching a crazy repetition :@@EndBracket@@ } 31... Rf7 32. Qe8+ Rf8 33. Qe6+
{ Again reaching a crazy repetition :@@EndBracket@@ } *

