1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine deeply the lines where White plays 6. Be2, a very normal move that you will face in many of your games. It is actually the most played move after 5...Be7, so definitely a chapter that is worth paying attention to! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Be2
{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Re1
{ white wants to protect the e4 pawn without weakening the kingside with the move f3. At this point we suggest two different ways to play with the black pieces so you can decide which one is your cup of tea. }
8... Bf8 { The mainline by far. } 9. Bf1 { the main continuation. } 9... c6
{ Black controls d5 and also prepares a possible expansion on the queenside. }
10. a4 { stopping black's expansion on the queenside. } 10... Nbd7
{ I tried to make work the natural 10...a5, but I could not. The knight now could land on c5 targetting e4 or even go to e5 and g6. }
11. a5 { Perhaps the most logical move, restricting the queenside. } 11... h6
{ preparing Nc5 and avoiding nasty pins on g5. } 12. h3 Nc5 13. Qf3 Qe7
{ If you run the engine, the first minute will tell you that Qe7 is a blunder and white has a decisive advantage, but let it run until deep 45, and then it will tell you that is the best move of the position!   In fact, taking the e4-pawn is possible, and black has a nice position after a fantastic exchange sacrifice!.   13...d5!?  is also playable  14.e5  Nh7 }
14. Bf4 Ncxe4 15. Qd3 d5 16. f3 Nc5 17. Rxe7 Nxd3 18. Rxe8 Nxf4
{ this leads to an exchange sacrifice! } 19. Ree1 c5 20. Nde2 Ne6
{ and this unbalanced position is around equal. Black has a piece and a pawn + bishop pair for the rook. It also enjoys a nice center! I would go without blinking for this position in an important game. An sample line could be }
21. Rad1 d4 22. Ne4 Nxe4 23. fxe4 Bd6 24. c3 Bc7 25. cxd4 Bxa5 26. d5 Bxe1 27.
Rxe1 Nf8
{ and white is almost equalizing but it still has to prove compensation for the pawn. }
