1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine deeply the lines where White plays 6. Be2, a very normal move that you will face in many of your games. It is actually the most played move after 5...Be7, so definitely a chapter that is worth paying attention to! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Be2
{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Re1
{ white wants to protect the e4 pawn without weakening the kingside with the move f3. At this point we suggest two different ways to play with the black pieces so you can decide which one is your cup of tea. }
8... Bf8 { The mainline by far. } 9. Bf1 { the main continuation. } 9... c6
{ Black controls d5 and also prepares a possible expansion on the queenside. }
10. Bg5 { the most played move, pinning the f6 knight. } 10... Nbd7 11. Qd2
{ this is white's most common idea, just connecting the rooks. } 11... h6
{ It is very nice for us that almost everybody went for } 12. Bh4
{ which leads to great positions for black. Important to note that at this moment almost everybody went for Ne5 but }
12... g5
{ is much stronger!!. Let's grab the bishop pair! Nothing to be afraid of! }
13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Rad1 Nxg3 15. fxg3
{ was seen in Kovanova,B @@StartBracket@@2376@@EndBracket@@-Batsiashvili,N @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Riga 2017 and we suggest the novelty }
15... Qb6 16. Na4 Qc7
{ and black has a fantastic position. The knight can land on f6 and a rook on e5 and the bishops will go to g7 and d7. Finally, the a8-rook can join the party to increase the pressure along the e-file. }
