[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine deeply the lines where White plays 6. Be2, a very normal move that you will face in many of your games. It is actually the most played move after 5...Be7, so definitely a chapter that is worth paying attention to! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Be2
{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. f4
{ this is the most played line by far. White initiates an attack on the kingside. Now the white bishop will be well placed on f3. }
8... c5
{ We deviate from the main line which is  8...Bf8  . Only about 100 games with  8...c5  and 600 with  8...Bf8  . We increase the chances to surprise our opponent.   By playing c5 black gets a backward pawn on d6, but we get an important tempo by kicking this knight on d4.  Moreover, the b8 knight can be developed now via c6. }
9. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black will combine the pressure on e4 with a queenside expansion and a liberating d5.   By playing  a6  , black will force  a4  in many cases, leaving a tasty  b4  square for a knight.  9...Bf8  is a big mistake because of  10.e5!  dxe5  11.Qxd8  and the bishop cannot take on d8 now. Black is worse. }
10. h3 { and we propose the novelty } 10... Bf8
{ has been played in every game in the database. Everybody went wrong! It is inaccurate because of }
11. e5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. fxe5 Nd7 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Rad1
{ and white is much better.   There are so many nasty ideas: e6, Bc4, etc. } *

