8... c5
{ We deviate from the main line which is  8...Bf8  . Only about 100 games with  8...c5  and 600 with  8...Bf8  . We increase the chances to surprise our opponent.   By playing c5 black gets a backward pawn on d6, but we get an important tempo by kicking this knight on d4.  Moreover, the b8 knight can be developed now via c6. }
9. Nb3
{ the most played line. White leaves the f3 square free for the bishop. } 9...
Nc6 10. Bf3 { 10.Kh1  Bf8  11.Bf3  transposes. } 10... Bf8 11. h3 Bd7
{ very attractive move seen in Jerez Perez, A @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@-Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2537@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Barcelona 2017. Black wants to play Rb8 and b5. The bishop on d7 stops white's e5 ideas targetting the c6 knight. }
12. Kh2 { and here we propose the novelty } 12... a5
{ Even stronger that Rb8!   The idea is to provoque a4 and then guarantee the b4 spot for the knight where attacks c2 and controls d5.   12...Rb8  was the game. }
13. a4 Nb4 14. Re1 Bc6 15. Bd2 g6 { Black has improved the two bishops now. }
16. Re2 Nd7
{ With a great position.   Ideas: bishop to g7, knight to b6 and then push d5 or jump to c4. }
