{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. f4
{ this is the most played line by far. White initiates an attack on the kingside. Now the white bishop will be well placed on f3. }
8... c5
{ We deviate from the main line which is  8...Bf8  . Only about 100 games with  8...c5  and 600 with  8...Bf8  . We increase the chances to surprise our opponent.   By playing c5 black gets a backward pawn on d6, but we get an important tempo by kicking this knight on d4.  Moreover, the b8 knight can be developed now via c6. }
9. Nb3
{ the most played line. White leaves the f3 square free for the bishop. } 9...
Nc6 10. Bf3 { 10.Kh1  Bf8  11.Bf3  transposes. } 10... Bf8 11. Kh1 a5
{ forcing a4, to get our tasty square on b4. } 12. a4 Nb4 13. Re1
{ The most human move to the human eye and the most played one @@StartBracket@@even by a couple of GMs@@EndBracket@@, but it is a poor choice due to }
13... d5 { boom! using that c2 is under attack. } 14. e5
{ 14.Nd2?!  Bf5!  with a clear advantage. } 14... Bf5
{ another great intermediate move targetting c2. } 15. Re2 d4 16. Nb5
{ 16.exf6?!  dxc3  Black is winning. } 16... Ng4
{ Now the queen can come to h4, where not only threatens checkmate on h2 but also supports the fork on f2. }
17. h3
{ If  17.g3  h5!  and Black blocks the king side!   The knight can always jump to h6 after h3. }
17... Qh4 18. c3
{ was seen in Hansen,L @@StartBracket@@1848@@EndBracket@@-Zuev,D ICCF email ½-½ 2009 and here we suggest the novelty }
18... Rad8 { 18...Nf2  is enough for an advantage too. } 19. cxb4
{ 19.cxd4  Nf2+  20.Rxf2  Qxf2  and Black's material superiority is enough for an advantage. }
19... d3 20. Bxg4
{ If  20.Rd2  then  Nxe5!  Is a bomb.  21.fxe5  Rxe5  and White cannot stop Re1 }
20... dxe2 21. Qxe2 Bxg4 22. Qxg4 Qe1+ 23. Kh2 Rd1 24. Nxc5
{ The best move according to the engines for White is  24.Bd2  but after  Qg1+  25.Kg3  Rxa1  26.Nxa1  Qxa1  Black is better. }
24... h5 { This is a great move to avoid white's king escape through h5 after }
25. Qxh5 Bxc5 26. bxc5 Qg1+ 27. Kg3 Rd3+ { and Black wins. } *

