{ happened in Stronsky,V @@StartBracket@@2429@@EndBracket@@-Ivanov,B @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 ICCF email 2014 and we deviate from the game with the novelty }
15... Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Nf8
{ with a nice position to play. Ideas: Qb6-Rb8-a5 and Ng6-Nh4 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Philidor Systems with 6.Be2"]
[Black "Systems with 6.Be2 and 8.f4 #44"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we examine deeply the lines where White plays 6. Be2, a very normal move that you will face in many of your games. It is actually the most played move after 5...Be7, so definitely a chapter that is worth paying attention to! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Nxd4 Be7 6. Be2
{ White develops a minor piece and is ready to castle. In these types of set-ups, we will usually use the e-file to put pressure on the e4 pawn combining this idea with some counterplay on the queenside. Moves like c6 or even c5 gaining a tempo on the d4 knight will come into consideration sooner or later. White will usually push f4 very soon. }
6... O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. f4
{ this is the most played line by far. White initiates an attack on the kingside. Now the white bishop will be well placed on f3. }
8... c5
{ We deviate from the main line which is  8...Bf8  . Only about 100 games with  8...c5  and 600 with  8...Bf8  . We increase the chances to surprise our opponent.   By playing c5 black gets a backward pawn on d6, but we get an important tempo by kicking this knight on d4.  Moreover, the b8 knight can be developed now via c6. }
9. Nb3
{ the most played line. White leaves the f3 square free for the bishop. } 9...
Nc6 10. Bf3 { 10.Kh1  Bf8  11.Bf3  transposes. } 10... Bf8 11. Re1 c4
{ 11...a5!?  Is also very attractive reaching similar positions to the ones we just analyzed  12.a4  Nb4 }
12. Nd4 d5 { again this central push is possible. } 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. e5
{ the main continuation. } 14... Nd7 15. Be3 { Profilaxis against Qb6. } 15...
Rb8 { targetting b2 } 16. Qc1
{ Was seen in Zielinski,S @@StartBracket@@2192@@EndBracket@@ -Vujadinovic,M @@StartBracket@@2085@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ LSS email 2008 and we suggest the novelty.   16.b3?!  is dubious because of  Bb4-+ }
16... f6
{ it is time to strike with f6 to break white's pawn center. There are some tactical tricks related with the bishop on e3 and the diagonal a7-g1. }
17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Bxa7 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Rxb2
{ And Black has a great position and clear advantage. The better structure and more active pieces guarantee a comfortable game. }
*

