1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Welcome back to another exciting chapter!   On this occasion, we analyze the super aggressive move 5.Rg1!? which prepares 6.g4.   I have faced this line in several rapid games and one classical game against my friend GM Daniel Alsina at the Portuguese league some years ago.   Let's start! }
5. Rg1 g6 { The mainline. Black will go for the fianchetto on many occasions. }
6. Be3
{ Is a new order that Fedossev has tried very recently in 2021 in online tournaments.   On many occasions, it can transpose to 6.g4. Now I recommend you to play }
6... c6 { is another possibility. } 7. g4
{ was played by Fedoseev in a couple of games and here we suggest } 7... h5 8.
h3 { the best move, controlling the g4 square. } 8... hxg4 9. hxg4 Nb6
{ black attacks the g4 pawn. } 10. Bg5 Be7 11. dxe5 Nxg4 12. Bxe7 Kxe7
{ King Leonidas came to protect d6! } 13. e6
{ is a dangerous try. Black should play } 13... Ne5
{ 13...Bxe6?!  14.Ng5!  and Black is in trouble. } 14. Nxe5
{ 14.exf7?  runs into  Bg4-+ } 14... dxe5 15. exf7 Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Kxf7
{ and the endgame is about equal. Be6 is coming.   The king is always safe on g7 and Rh6 can be played to protect g6 if needed. }
