1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Welcome back to another exciting chapter!   On this occasion, we analyze the super aggressive move 5.Rg1!? which prepares 6.g4.   I have faced this line in several rapid games and one classical game against my friend GM Daniel Alsina at the Portuguese league some years ago.   Let's start! }
5. Rg1 g6 { The mainline. Black will go for the fianchetto on many occasions. }
6. g4
{ is the move that almost everybody played @@StartBracket@@61 out of 66 games@@EndBracket@@. }
6... exd4
{ We deviate from the mainline which is  6...Bg7  because I could not fully equalize. This move has been played only in 2 games so it will probably surprise your opponent and it is also the best according to the engines. }
7. Nxd4 Bg7 8. g5
{ makes a lot of sense at this moment and it looks like white is winning. The knight on h5 would be easily attacked with Be2, so what can we do? Black is fine because tactics are favourable after }
8... Nxe4 { boom! } 9. Nxe4 Qe7 10. f3 d5
{ White should be very careful and there is only one move that equalizes. } 11.
Nb5 Nb6
{ Leading to crazy complications!   11...dxe4!?  is super interesting as well. You can analyze it at home if you want to know more. }
12. Bf4 { White must insist on the c7 square. } 12... O-O 13. Nxc7
{ black should cover the d6-square. } 13... Rd8 14. Nxa8 dxe4 15. Qe2 Nd5
{ black is a whole rook down but is getting some material back very soon. } 16.
O-O-O
{ and black can decide now if it plays for the win or make an immediate draw. }
16... Bxb2+ 17. Kxb2 Qb4+ { perpetual. } *

