1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Welcome back to another exciting chapter!   On this occasion, we analyze the super aggressive move 5.Rg1!? which prepares 6.g4.   I have faced this line in several rapid games and one classical game against my friend GM Daniel Alsina at the Portuguese league some years ago.   Let's start! }
5. Rg1 g6 { The mainline. Black will go for the fianchetto on many occasions. }
6. g4
{ is the move that almost everybody played @@StartBracket@@61 out of 66 games@@EndBracket@@. }
6... exd4
{ We deviate from the mainline which is  6...Bg7  because I could not fully equalize. This move has been played only in 2 games so it will probably surprise your opponent and it is also the best according to the engines. }
7. Nxd4 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. g5
{ The best move, kicking the knight back and gaining some space. } 9... Ne8 10.
f4 { This novelty is the first recommendation of Stockfish12. } 10... Nb6 11.
Qd2 c5
{ Black should react, otherwise we will suffer if we remain passive on the 7th and back rank. }
12. Nf3 Bd7 13. O-O-O Qe7
{ Black targets e4. Bxc3 followed by Qxe4 can be a threat. } 14. e5
{ is interesting since the cost of getting the e5 pawn would be to high for black. The dar squared bishop is a very important piece. }
14... d5
{ and white cannot capture since after the trades, Bc6 would win the game on the spot. }
15. Bf2 Nc7
{ with a very double edged position where I really like black's perspectives. The idea is to proceed with Bc6 and d4. }
