1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ Welcome back to another exciting chapter!   On this occasion, we analyze the super aggressive move 5.Rg1!? which prepares 6.g4.   I have faced this line in several rapid games and one classical game against my friend GM Daniel Alsina at the Portuguese league some years ago.   Let's start! }
5. Rg1 g6 { The mainline. Black will go for the fianchetto on many occasions. }
6. g4
{ is the move that almost everybody played @@StartBracket@@61 out of 66 games@@EndBracket@@. }
6... exd4
{ We deviate from the mainline which is  6...Bg7  because I could not fully equalize. This move has been played only in 2 games so it will probably surprise your opponent and it is also the best according to the engines. }
7. Nxd4 Bg7 8. Be3 O-O 9. g5
{ The best move, kicking the knight back and gaining some space. } 9... Ne8 10.
Qd2
{ was seen in Milosevic,M @@StartBracket@@2249@@EndBracket@@-Morozov,N @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Tarvisio 2017. We deviate from the game with }
10... c5 { and white has an only move here. } 11. Nb3 a5
{ black threatens a4 followed by a3. } 12. a4 Qe7 13. O-O-O Nb6
{ and the a4 pawn is weak. Bxc3 followed by Nxa4 is a threat and also the simple Bd7. }
14. Bb5 { profilaxis against Bd7. } 14... Bd7 15. Bxd7
{ and black has two options now. } 15... Nxd7
{ is the one that I prefer because it leads to complicated variations. Bxc3 followed by Qxe4 is a present idea. White has now three reasonable choices. }
16. f3
{ is perhaps the most natural move protecting the e4 pawn. Now black has two interesting choices. }
16... b5 { asking where is the party. } 17. Bf4
{ This not-human move is the best try for white. } 17... bxa4 18. Nxa4 Ne5 19.
Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Rge1 c4 21. Nd4 Qe7
{ with a double edged position. Black intends to bring the queen to b7 with a fun position to play. }
*

