{ The best move, kicking the knight back and gaining some space. } 9... Ne8 10.
Qd2
{ was seen in Milosevic,M @@StartBracket@@2249@@EndBracket@@-Morozov,N @@StartBracket@@2467@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Tarvisio 2017. We deviate from the game with }
10... c5 { and white has an only move here. } 11. Nb3 a5
{ black threatens a4 followed by a3. } 12. a4 Qe7 13. O-O-O Nb6
{ and the a4 pawn is weak. Bxc3 followed by Nxa4 is a threat and also the simple Bd7. }
14. Bb5 { profilaxis against Bd7. } 14... Bd7 15. Bxd7
{ and black has two options now. } 15... Nxd7
{ is the one that I prefer because it leads to complicated variations. Bxc3 followed by Qxe4 is a present idea. White has now three reasonable choices. }
16. Rge1 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qxe4 18. Bxc5 Qxa4 19. Bd4 Qb5 20. h4 a4 21. Nd2 d5
{ And again we have reached a very double edged position.   I think I would take black pieces because it looks like the attack is faster. Nd6 and Rfc8 is coming very fast.  Once the queen is not on the h8-a1 diagonal black will not have to worry about mates on g7. We have arrived to the end of the chapter. And I hope you guys have enjoyed the recipe I propose.   I think the positions are very fun to play and hopefully these fresh ideas will help you to get nice positions. And remember! If you have any questions, leave a comment.   I am here to answer all of them! :@@EndBracket@@ }
