[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. h3
{ In this chapter we study the move 5.h3, a very aggressive try from white.   Usually, the idea will be to push g4 immediately or near future, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.  Strong GMs such as Antipov or Krasenkow, went for this variation.   This is one of my favorite chapters since black will sacrifice pawns and pieces in many lines! }
5... Be7 6. Be3 { is the other serious move for white here. } 6... c6
{ Black starts with this move delaying castling. It prepares a queenside expansion as usual. }
7. Qd2 { If white allows b5 we should go for it! } 7... b5
{ b4 is threatened. } 8. a3 O-O 9. g4 { 9.Bd3  transposes. } 9... Bb7
{ Black prepares a5 followed by b4. c5 is also an idea in certain positions. There are 5 games with this position and in all of them, white went for }
10. g5 { and Black must play the strong intermediate move } 10... exd4 11. Qxd4
Ne8
{ Nc7 is coming and then a5 followed by b4 or even c5 are attractive choices. }
12. Bg2 Nc7 13. h4 a5 14. O-O
{ it is clear that the white king would be even less comfortable on the queenside. }
14... c5 { followed by f6, with a very nice position. } *

