1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. h3
{ In this chapter we study the move 5.h3, a very aggressive try from white.   Usually, the idea will be to push g4 immediately or near future, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.  Strong GMs such as Antipov or Krasenkow, went for this variation.   This is one of my favorite chapters since black will sacrifice pawns and pieces in many lines! }
5... Be7 6. g4 { 6.Bc4  transposes to the main lines of the course. } 6... h6
{ Profilaxis. White has employed three moves mainly at this stage.   I think White is better if Black plays  6...O-O  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be2+= }
7. Bc4
{ is a dangerous try. White wants to push g5 and place a knight on that square in order to attack the f7 pawn. }
7... c6 8. Bb3
{ is a smart try and a profilactic move against d5 in the lines that white goes for g5 followed by Ng5. }
8... b5
{ asking white to go for g5, which is what we want! In the two games with this position, white took the bait! }
9. g5 hxg5 10. Nxg5 O-O
{ black is safe and white has not developed anything yet. } 11. dxe5
{ was seen in Croese,C @@StartBracket@@2363@@EndBracket@@-Lathouwers,R  @@StartBracket@@2214@@EndBracket@@ 1-0 Haarlem 2008 and we propose to continue with }
11... Nxe5 12. f4 Ng6 { and black is ready to open up the position with d5. }
13. Be3 a5 { threatening a4. } 14. a4 b4 15. Ne2 d5 16. e5 Nh5
{ Black is aiming to take in f4 followed by Bxg5. } 17. h4 Bg4
{ and f4 will fall after taking on e2. Another idea is Qc8. The b3-bishop is perfectly neutralized. }
