{ In this chapter we study the move 5.h3, a very aggressive try from white.   Usually, the idea will be to push g4 immediately or near future, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.  Strong GMs such as Antipov or Krasenkow, went for this variation.   This is one of my favorite chapters since black will sacrifice pawns and pieces in many lines! }
5... Be7 6. g4 { 6.Bc4  transposes to the main lines of the course. } 6... h6
{ Profilaxis. White has employed three moves mainly at this stage.   I think White is better if Black plays  6...O-O  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be2+= }
7. Be3 { The critical line. } 7... c6 8. a4
{ the best try for white in my opinion, stopping b5. } 8... O-O
{ This novelty is our recommendation.   No fear!   In many variations, Black will react in the center pushing d5. exd4 will be included previously in certain lines. }
9. Qd2
{ White puts another piece supporting g5 and targetting h6. Black reacts with }
9... exd4 10. Bxd4 Ne5 11. Be2 { White does not accept the challenge on e5. }
11... Be6 { Black is ready to capture on f3 followed by d5. } 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13.
Qxd8 Raxd8 14. Nxe5 Bc5 { Black threatens Bd4 followed by Bxc3 and Nxe4. } 15.
Nd3 Bd4 16. f3 a5
{ And the pawn is highly compensated. The engines say this position is 0.00.   The dark squared bishop is fantastic. Ideas: Nd7-g6-Rfe8-Ne5-f5, etc. White will never castle comfortably on the queenside since a4 would suffer. }
*

