[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. h3
{ In this chapter we study the move 5.h3, a very aggressive try from white.   Usually, the idea will be to push g4 immediately or near future, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.  Strong GMs such as Antipov or Krasenkow, went for this variation.   This is one of my favorite chapters since black will sacrifice pawns and pieces in many lines! }
5... Be7 6. g4 { 6.Bc4  transposes to the main lines of the course. } 6... h6
{ Profilaxis. White has employed three moves mainly at this stage.   I think White is better if Black plays  6...O-O  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be2+= }
7. Be3 { The critical line. } 7... c6 8. Qd2
{ the most played move. White prepares for long castle. } 8... b5
{ Black starts an attack already on the queenside and it is inviting white to go for long castle. b4 followed by Nxe4 is the threat now. }
9. Bd3 Qc7 10. Ne2
{ Was seen in Anjali,R @@StartBracket@@1873@@EndBracket@@-Mc Aleenan,C 1-0@@StartBracket@@1795@@EndBracket@@ Marianske Lazne 2015.   White intends to bring the knight to g3 looking for the f5 square. Morover white can reinforce the center with c3. As usual, whenever the knight stops controlling the d5 square black can react with.   10.a3  a5  transposes to 9.a3 }
10... d5 11. Ng3 dxe4 12. Bxe4
{ 12.Nxe4?!  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  Nf6=+  and White is in trouble since there is a fork on e4. }
12... Bb7
{ And the position is double edged. Taking on e4 followed O-O-O is an idea.   White should always pay atenttion to the c5 push opening the diagonal for the light squared bishop. }
*

