1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. h3
{ In this chapter we study the move 5.h3, a very aggressive try from white.   Usually, the idea will be to push g4 immediately or near future, starting a dangerous attack on the kingside.  Strong GMs such as Antipov or Krasenkow, went for this variation.   This is one of my favorite chapters since black will sacrifice pawns and pieces in many lines! }
5... Be7 6. g4 { 6.Bc4  transposes to the main lines of the course. } 6... h6
{ Profilaxis. White has employed three moves mainly at this stage.   I think White is better if Black plays  6...O-O  7.g5  Nh5  8.Be2+= }
7. Be3 { The critical line. } 7... c6 8. Qd2
{ the most played move. White prepares for long castle. } 8... b5
{ Black starts an attack already on the queenside and it is inviting white to go for long castle. b4 followed by Nxe4 is the threat now. }
9. a3 a5 { Again we stop long castling since b4 would come with real pain. }
10. Bd3 Qc7
{ The plan is to play Bb7 followed by b4 if white does nothing about that. }
11. Ne2 d5 { again black reacts in the center. } 12. Ng3 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Bb7
{ and black is fine. Nxe4 followed by 0-0-0 is a way to proceed. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Philidor 5.g3"]
[Black "Philidor 5.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g3
{ This move is not considered to be especially dangerous from the theoretical point of view but of course it is very playable and it has been employed by different strong GMs including Mamedov, Efimenko and Granda among others.   White simply wants to play Bg2 followed by the short castle. }
5... Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6
{ You probably have seen this move in many chapters.   Black controls the d5 square and prepares a queenside expansion. }
8. a4 { The only reasonable move for white, stopping Black's counterplay. }
8... b6
{ This is one of my favorite plans of the Philidor.   By playing 8...b6 black stops white's a5 and prepares a slow expansion on the queenside. The idea is to play Bb7 followed by a6 and b5 in the future.   Naturally, Black cannot hurry up with the move  8...a6  since  9.a5  is very strong positionally.  At this point, we analyze four different options that white tried. }
9. b3 { White goes for the double fianchetto. } 9... Bb7 10. Bb2 Qc7 11. Qd2
{ 11.Re1  transposes. } 11... Rfe8 12. Rad1 a6
{ And Black has good play. The idea is to play b5 followed by Rad8 and Bf8.   The bishop can be recycled on g7 at some point. This is the formation that you will see in many variations and it is pretty easy to remember. }
*

