1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g3
{ This move is not considered to be especially dangerous from the theoretical point of view but of course it is very playable and it has been employed by different strong GMs including Mamedov, Efimenko and Granda among others.   White simply wants to play Bg2 followed by the short castle. }
5... Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6
{ You probably have seen this move in many chapters.   Black controls the d5 square and prepares a queenside expansion. }
8. a4 { The only reasonable move for white, stopping Black's counterplay. }
8... b6
{ This is one of my favorite plans of the Philidor.   By playing 8...b6 black stops white's a5 and prepares a slow expansion on the queenside. The idea is to play Bb7 followed by a6 and b5 in the future.   Naturally, Black cannot hurry up with the move  8...a6  since  9.a5  is very strong positionally.  At this point, we analyze four different options that white tried. }
9. Re1 Bb7 10. h3 a6 11. Nh4 g6 { Nf5 needs to be stopped! } 12. Bh6 Re8 13.
Qd2 { Black should be careful about Nf5 ideas followed by Qg5. } 13... Bf8 14.
Bxf8 Nxf8
{ Black is very solid.   The plan is to continue with b5. As you have seen, memory is not very important in this chapter and black has a clear plan: c6-b6-Bb7-a6-b5-Re8-Bf8-Qc7.   Depending on the order white employs, black will start with one or another move but the plan is basically always the same.   Hope you guys have enjoyed and thanks a lot for reading! See you in the next chapter! }
