[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Philidor 3.Nc3 4.Nf3 followed by 5.Be2"]
[Black "3.Nc3 4.Nf3 5.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze the move 5.Be2.   When our opponents go for these set-ups, it usually means that they do not have a clue of how to fight against the Philidor or that they do not want to enter in the theoretical lines for some reason.   The c4 square is a much better one for the bishop since from there it attacks f7, which is the weakest Black square. This is why this move is considered to be less critical but anyway there are more than 1000 games with this line, so definitely deserve serious attention.   It is a normal developing move and White gets ready to castle.   I am pretty sure you will see it pretty often in your games, so let's study how to handle these positions! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Be2 Be7 6. g4
{ Is a very serious try! Once the black bishop is developed to e7, g7 can suffer if the g-file gets opened. }
6... Nxg4
{ No fear! Black can take the pawn.  6...h6!?  is the mainline and also playable. }
7. Rg1 Nb6
{ There is only one game and not between strong players so I am pretty sure you would have brought your opponent out of theory by this point already. }
8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Bxd8 11. Rxg7 Be6
{ Black is very solid and ready to kick the g7-rook after Bf6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Philidor 3.Nc3 4.Nf3 followed by 5.Be2"]
[Black "3.Nc3 4.Nf3 5.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze the move 5.Be2.   When our opponents go for these set-ups, it usually means that they do not have a clue of how to fight against the Philidor or that they do not want to enter in the theoretical lines for some reason.   The c4 square is a much better one for the bishop since from there it attacks f7, which is the weakest Black square. This is why this move is considered to be less critical but anyway there are more than 1000 games with this line, so definitely deserve serious attention.   It is a normal developing move and White gets ready to castle.   I am pretty sure you will see it pretty often in your games, so let's study how to handle these positions! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Be2 Be7 6. g4
{ Is a very serious try! Once the black bishop is developed to e7, g7 can suffer if the g-file gets opened. }
6... Nxg4
{ No fear! Black can take the pawn.  6...h6!?  is the mainline and also playable. }
7. Rg1 Nb6
{ There is only one game and not between strong players so I am pretty sure you would have brought your opponent out of theory by this point already. }
8. a4
{ white threatens to push a5 and therefore the g4 knight since d7 is the only available square for the knight. }
8... a5 9. h3 exd4 { nice intermediate move. } 10. Nxd4
{ 10.Qxd4?!  allows  Bf6!=+  followed by Ne5, and g7 does not fall. } 10... Ne5
11. Rxg7
{ This is the same exact position as in the mainline but with the inclusion of a4 and a5. This creates a weak square on b5 and black cannot go for Bh4 followed by Qf6. Therefore black should play }
11... Bxh3 { 11...Bh4?!  12.Be3  Qf6  13.Rg1  Be6  14.Ndb5+- } 12. Rg3
{ 12.Be3  h5  @@StartBracket@@intending Bg4 trapping the rook@@EndBracket@@  13.Rg3  transposes. }
12... Bd7 13. Be3 h5 14. Nf5
{ White cannot continue development in the natural way with  14.Qd2?  because of  Nec4-+ }
14... Bxf5 15. exf5 h4 16. Rg1 h3 { Run run! } 17. Bxb6 cxb6 18. Nd5 Bh4
{ and some tactical shots appear on f2. } 19. Qd2 h2 20. Rh1 Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2
Qh4+ 22. Kf1 { and Black has a draw if wanted. } 22... Qh3+
{ 22...O-O-O!?  is playable to go for the win. You can take a look at home. }
23. Ke1 Qg3+ 24. Kf1 { is innacurate and black has good chances after } 24...
Rg8 { threatening mate on g1. } 25. Nf6+ Ke7 26. Qxd6+ Kxd6 27. Ne4+ Ke7 28.
Nxg3 Rxg3
{ and Black has a better endgame because the f5 pawn is very weak and a Black has a better king. }
