{ was seen in Michalczak, T @@StartBracket@@2163@@EndBracket@@-Pewny, U @@StartBracket@@2203@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Germany 2019 and I suggest the strong novelty }
10... Ng6 { being greedy going for the exchange is inaccurate. } 11. Bh6 Bf6
12. Qd2 { and the dark-squared bishop will be too strong. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Philidor 3.Nc3 4.Nf3 followed by 5.Be2"]
[Black "3.Nc3 4.Nf3 5.Be2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ In this chapter we analyze the move 5.Be2.   When our opponents go for these set-ups, it usually means that they do not have a clue of how to fight against the Philidor or that they do not want to enter in the theoretical lines for some reason.   The c4 square is a much better one for the bishop since from there it attacks f7, which is the weakest Black square. This is why this move is considered to be less critical but anyway there are more than 1000 games with this line, so definitely deserve serious attention.   It is a normal developing move and White gets ready to castle.   I am pretty sure you will see it pretty often in your games, so let's study how to handle these positions! }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Be2 Be7 6. g4
{ Is a very serious try! Once the black bishop is developed to e7, g7 can suffer if the g-file gets opened. }
6... Nxg4
{ No fear! Black can take the pawn.  6...h6!?  is the mainline and also playable. }
7. Rg1 Nb6
{ There is only one game and not between strong players so I am pretty sure you would have brought your opponent out of theory by this point already. }
8. h3
{ is the most natural move and the one that most of the people would play instantaneously. And the good thing is that it is not the best move and black gets an edge! }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Ne5 10. Rxg7
{ was seen in Michalczak, T @@StartBracket@@2163@@EndBracket@@-Pewny, U @@StartBracket@@2203@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 Germany 2019 and I suggest the strong novelty }
10... Bh4
{ The queen will come to f6, kicking the rook and there will be big pressure against f2, making hard for white to castle. }
11. Be3 Qf6 12. Rg1 Be6
{ black is slightly better and ready to castle alongside. h3 is always a weakness and in case white takes on e6, black is ready to fix the pawn structure after fxe6. c4 is a tasty square and f2 is suffering a lot. }
*

