{ And from this point we divide the chapter into two parts.   We first analyze the lines where White goes  7.Bc4  and then the lines where White does not play 7.Bc4 and instead tries to rapidly develop the queenside.   Both are very dangerous. }
7. Be3 { White's idea is to play 8.Qd2 and 9.O-O-O } 7... c6
{ a very useful move preparing b5. } 8. Qd2
{ And now I give you two interesting options.  8...b5  which is the mainline and  8...Qe7!?  which is almost a novelty and will probably bring your opponent out of the book. }
8... Qe7
{ This move has only been played only twice, and never by a GM. Hopefully one of you readers will be the third person to play it!   It is a very interesting and fresh idea.   The queen protects f7 and Black wants to develop the dark-squared bishop via g7. }
9. O-O-O g6 { From this point, White has tried five different moves. } 10. Bc4
{ Helps Black's plan. } 10... Nb6 11. Bb3 Be6
{ trading the powerful b3-bishop. } 12. Ng5 Bxb3 13. axb3 Bg7 14. dxe5 dxe5 15.
f4 O-O 16. fxe5 Nh5
{ and Black will eventually collect the e5-pawn, with a good position. } *

