[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. Philidor Shirov 5.g4"]
[Black "Philidor Shirov 5.g4, 7.Bc4 and 8.Nxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome back to a new chapter!   This is probably the wildest one in the whole course.   White goes for an extremely aggressive approach with 5.g4!?, a move that came into fashion thanks to Alexey Shirov, who employed it for the first time in 2003 against Azmaiparashvili. Since then, it became very popular and has been tried by many players against the Philidor.   It has a lot of venom and we should really know what to do with the black pieces. I have worked very hard and found different novelties that hopefully will help you.   Hope you enjoy all the crazy variations that are going to arise! }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ Straight to the jugular.   White sacrifices a pawn and will get a lot of counterplay along the g-file, making it difficult for Black to develop the f8-bishop in many variations.   Black should take the pawn }
5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6
{ And from this point we divide the chapter into two parts.   We first analyze the lines where White goes  7.Bc4  and then the lines where White does not play 7.Bc4 and instead tries to rapidly develop the queenside.   Both are very dangerous. }
7. Bc4
{ Perhaps the most natural move. White is already threatening to win with the move Ng5 because f7 suffers. Now we give two interesting alternatives for black. }
7... exd4
{ Our second recommendation. This capture has been played by two gods of the Philidor defence: GM Strikovic and GM Paunovic. Black frees the e5 square for the knight. }
8. Nxd4
{ a very reasonable move too. White could push f4 in the future. At this point, I give you two decent choices to proceed. }
8... c6
{ This novelty makes sense. Black controls d5 and prepare a queenside expansion with b5. It also frees the d8-a5 diagonal for the queen. }
9. Bf4 Qb6 { attacking b2. } 10. Bb3 Ne5
{ black threatens a nasty trick on d4 using a fork on f3. } 11. Nf3 Nfg4
{ this move creates more chaos! } 12. Bg3
{ this natural move is a clear mistake and runs into } 12... Ne3 { Ratatatata }
13. Qe2 Nxc2+ { White queen is overloaded. } 14. Bxc2 Qxb2 15. Kd2 Bg4
{ another great intermediate move pinning f3. } 16. Bxe5 dxe5
{ with long castle to follow! } 17. Rab1 O-O-O+ 18. Nd5 Bxf3
{ how many intermediate moves? :@@EndBracket@@ } 19. Qxf3 Bb4+ 20. Kd1 Qd4+ 21.
Ke2 cxd5
{ and Black gets the piece back with some extra pawns and a better king. } *

