{ White starts developing the queenside, because its short term plan is to castle longside. Black will struggle developing the kingside because of the pressure along the g-file. That is why black main moves will be focused on the queenside. }
8... c6
{ a very typical move that we have seen many times. Black controls d5, and prepares an expansion on the queenside with b5. }
9. Qd3
{ The queen on d3 makes more sense than on d2. First of all, protects e4 and after some black's b4, the queen could come to c4 targetting f7, as we will see in some crazy lines. }
9... b5 10. Bb3 Qa5
{ the queen on a5 is well placed. It protects the a6 square, where a bishop will land. That means that b4 will be a real threat in such positions. }
11. O-O-O { 11.dxe5  transposes to the main line. } 11... Ba6
{ now b4 comes into consideration. } 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nd2
{ this is the main line and the only correct move for white. } 13... Rd8
{ the rook looks with X-rays to the queen on d3. White has tried two moves in this position. }
