{ Welcome back to a new chapter!   This is probably the wildest one in the whole course.   White goes for an extremely aggressive approach with 5.g4!?, a move that came into fashion thanks to Alexey Shirov, who employed it for the first time in 2003 against Azmaiparashvili. Since then, it became very popular and has been tried by many players against the Philidor.   It has a lot of venom and we should really know what to do with the black pieces. I have worked very hard and found different novelties that hopefully will help you.   Hope you enjoy all the crazy variations that are going to arise! }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g4
{ Straight to the jugular.   White sacrifices a pawn and will get a lot of counterplay along the g-file, making it difficult for Black to develop the f8-bishop in many variations.   Black should take the pawn }
5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6
{ And from this point we divide the chapter into two parts.   We first analyze the lines where White goes  7.Bc4  and then the lines where White does not play 7.Bc4 and instead tries to rapidly develop the queenside.   Both are very dangerous. }
7. Bc4
{ Perhaps the most natural move. White is already threatening to win with the move Ng5 because f7 suffers. Now we give two interesting alternatives for black. }
7... h6 { Prophylaxis against Ng5. The main line by far. } 8. Be3
{ White starts developing the queenside, because its short term plan is to castle longside. Black will struggle developing the kingside because of the pressure along the g-file. That is why black main moves will be focused on the queenside. }
8... c6
{ a very typical move that we have seen many times. Black controls d5, and prepares an expansion on the queenside with b5. }
9. Qd3
{ The queen on d3 makes more sense than on d2. First of all, protects e4 and after some black's b4, the queen could come to c4 targetting f7, as we will see in some crazy lines. }
9... b5 10. Bb3 Qa5
{ the queen on a5 is well placed. It protects the a6 square, where a bishop will land. That means that b4 will be a real threat in such positions. }
11. O-O-O { 11.dxe5  transposes to the main line. } 11... Ba6
{ now b4 comes into consideration. } 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nd2
{ this is the main line and the only correct move for white. } 13... Rd8
{ the rook looks with X-rays to the queen on d3. White has tried two moves in this position. }
14. Kb1 Nc5 15. Qf1
{ Again the queen has to go to a protected square so b4 is not decisive. Here we play the novelty }
15... b4 16. Nc4 Nxb3 17. axb3 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 Bxc4 19. bxc4
{ If  19.Qxc4  Qb5=+  offering a queen trade is healthy for Black. } 19... Nd7
{ with an equal and unclear position. } *

