{ In this chapter we cover a bunch of sharp lines in the Philidor.   I am talking about all variations where white sacrifices a bishop on f7.   The good news for us is that with concrete and precise play, Black can end up better out of the opening in many cases. This is not going to be the case in every chapter, and we will have to deal with some difficult positions as well.   Lets's get ready to rumble and have some fun with these crazy lines : }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ f7 is the weakest square in Black's position, so the bishop on c4 is perfectly placed }
5... Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5 O-O 8. Bxf7+ Rxf7 9. Ne6 Qe8 10. Nxc7 Qd8 11. Nxa8
b6 { Black regains the piece with an unclear position } 12. Nd5
{ is the mainline by far, but pretty inaccurate! White wants to bring the a8 knight via c7 }
12... Nxe4 13. Be3 { and here we suggest the novelty } 13... Bd6
{ keeping the knight in the corner } 14. f3 { 14.O-O  Ba6-+ } 14... Qh4+ 15. g3
Nxg3 16. Bf2 Bb7 17. Bxg3 Qc4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Philidor Sacrifices on f7"]
[Black "Sacrifices on f7 7.Bxf7+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter we cover a bunch of sharp lines in the Philidor.   I am talking about all variations where white sacrifices a bishop on f7.   The good news for us is that with concrete and precise play, Black can end up better out of the opening in many cases. This is not going to be the case in every chapter, and we will have to deal with some difficult positions as well.   Lets's get ready to rumble and have some fun with these crazy lines : }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ f7 is the weakest square in Black's position, so the bishop on c4 is perfectly placed }
5... Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Kg8 9. Ne6 Qe8 10. Nxc7 Qg6
{ In this variation where dxe5 has been included, White should take the rook on a8. }
11. Nxa8
{ 11.O-O?!  Rb8-+  reaching similar positions to the ones analyzed in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppnbppp/3p1n2/4p3/2BPP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bxf7  line. }
11... Qxg2 12. Rf1
{ The main difference with the line starting with 6.Bxf7 is that now we cannot use the e5 square for our knight, so this clearly favors White.   But White is not better by any means! }
12... Nc5
