{ In this chapter we cover a bunch of sharp lines in the Philidor.   I am talking about all variations where white sacrifices a bishop on f7.   The good news for us is that with concrete and precise play, Black can end up better out of the opening in many cases. This is not going to be the case in every chapter, and we will have to deal with some difficult positions as well.   Lets's get ready to rumble and have some fun with these crazy lines : }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ f7 is the weakest square in Black's position, so the bishop on c4 is perfectly placed }
5... Be7 6. Bxf7+ Kxf7
{ White sacrifices the bishop. In return, black's king is pretty exposed and a knight is going to land on c7 pretty soon! }
7. Ng5+ Kg8
{ On e8 or d8 Black loses the queen.   7...Kg6?!  We should not dance Salsa with the king in the middle of the board. }
8. Ne6 Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qg6 10. O-O
{ White does not allow Black to enter on g2, but of course now we are on time to save the rook! }
10... Rb8
{ White has some compensation for the piece: 2 pawns and a better king but with precise play, Black is clearly better. }
11. f4 { opening up the position } 11... h6
{ same idea! king on h7 and rook into play! } 12. f5 Qf7 13. d5 Bd8 14. Ne6
Bb6+ { black has managed to recycle the bishop! } 15. Kh1 Ba5
{ we will get rid of this bishop on c3, and finish development with b6 followed by Bb7. Even though there is still a lot of work to do, Black is clearly better. }
