{ On e8 or d8 Black loses the queen.   7...Kg6?!  We should not dance Salsa with the king in the middle of the board. }
8. Ne6 Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qg6 10. Nxa8
{ Probably the most natural move to the human eye, being greedy and getting back material immediately, but black is better after }
10... Qxg2 11. Rf1 exd4
{ The idea is to free the e5 square, so the d7 Knight and the c8 bishop can join the party! }
12. Qxd4 Ne5 { threatening a fork on f3 } 13. f3
{ Is the only move to try to survive. Now Black has to bring the e7 bishop to the battle.   There are two interesting ways to do it: }
13... Nfg4 { is also enough for an advantage. } 14. Qd5+ { only move } 14...
Nf7 15. Qc4
{ Again white's idea is to protect the rook on f1 so the king can run } 15...
Bh4+ 16. Kd1 Be6 17. Qe2 Nf2+ 18. Rxf2 Bxf2 19. Bf4
{ Only move to stay in the game } 19... Qg1+ 20. Kd2 Qxa1 21. Qxf2 h6 22. Nc7
Bd7
{ and black is better because of material superiority. Once the queen is back from holidays on a1, black will be able to consolidate the advantage. }
