[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Philidor Sacrifices on f7"]
[Black "Sacrifices on f7 6.Ng5 O-O 7.Bxf7+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter we cover a bunch of sharp lines in the Philidor.   I am talking about all variations where white sacrifices a bishop on f7.   The good news for us is that with concrete and precise play, Black can end up better out of the opening in many cases. This is not going to be the case in every chapter, and we will have to deal with some difficult positions as well.   Lets's get ready to rumble and have some fun with these crazy lines : }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ f7 is the weakest square in Black's position, so the bishop on c4 is perfectly placed }
5... Be7 6. Ng5 O-O 7. Bxf7+ Rxf7 8. Ne6
{ In this variation, Black has managed to castle, but the rook on f7 will avoid the queen coming to g6, where it was more active in the previous lines we showed.   8.Nxf7?  This is a very typical mistake that I have seen in beginners. Black is just better with the two pieces vs rook and the king is going back to g8 soon.  Kxf7-+ }
8... Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qd8 10. Nxa8
{ White is an exchange up plus two pawns at this point, but Black is going to capture the knight on a8 pretty soon }
10... b5 11. Nxb5
{ Being greedy does not help White in this position. Black is just much better after the following simple sequence: }
11... Qa5+ 12. Nc3 Nxe4 { using the pin on the a5-e1 diagonal. } 13. O-O Nxc3
14. bxc3 Bb7
{ And the knight on a8 falls. Black enjoys two pieces vs rook and a fantastic bishop pair! }
*

