[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Main Line 8.Qe2"]
[Black "Main line with 8.Qe2 and 11.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qe2
{ New chapter!   How is your energy battery? Hope still some power left!   On this occasion, we focus on this 8.Qe2 line. There are more than 400 games with this line in my database, therefore deserves serious attention.   White's idea is to free the d1-square for the rook. This line brings me good memories because I won a very important game with the black pieces and took clear first in 'La Roda' Open in 2011, probably one of the most important tournament victories in my career.   Whenever there is a queen on e2, it is interesting to open the e-file and put pressure on e4. That is why we play }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8
{ The idea is to place the bishop on f8 and put pressure on e4. d5 is a very typical reaction in these positions. }
10. Be3 { The second most played move. } 10... Bf8
{ Again putting pressure on e4. } 11. Nf3
{ The most accurate move, but is very difficult to spot over the board. White stops Nxe4 using the tactics on f7. }
11... h6
{ 11...Nxe4!?  is playable but only leads to equality  12.Nxe4  d5   12...Rxe4?  is met with  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Qd3+-  targetting h7 and d6.  13.Bxd5  cxd5  14.Nc3  Nf6=  with equality. }
12. Nd2 { solid but leaves the e5 available for our knight. } 12... Ne5 13. Bb3
Neg4 14. Bf4 d5
{ With a good position for Black. Once more, there are problems for White along the e-file. }
*

