1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qe2
{ New chapter!   How is your energy battery? Hope still some power left!   On this occasion, we focus on this 8.Qe2 line. There are more than 400 games with this line in my database, therefore deserves serious attention.   White's idea is to free the d1-square for the rook. This line brings me good memories because I won a very important game with the black pieces and took clear first in 'La Roda' Open in 2011, probably one of the most important tournament victories in my career.   Whenever there is a queen on e2, it is interesting to open the e-file and put pressure on e4. That is why we play }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8
{ The idea is to place the bishop on f8 and put pressure on e4. d5 is a very typical reaction in these positions. }
10. Ba2 { The mainline by far. It is a good prophylactic move against d5. }
10... Bf8 { and guess what? Yes, d5 is the idea. } 11. Qf3
{ White removes the queen from the e-file and keeps protecting the e4 pawn. Now we advocate two possibilities to continue. One is the main line and the second one is a super interesting novelty. }
11... h6 { is the first Stockfish 12 choice. Let's dig a little bit! } 12. h3
{ Prophylaxis covering the g4 square.   12.Re1?  runs into  d5! } 12... a5
{ fixing the structure on the queen side and guaranteeing the c5 and b6 squares for the black pieces. }
13. Qg3 Nc5 14. f3 d5
{ reaching a very similar position to the one analyzed before with the inclusion of h3 and a5. }
15. exd5
{ 15.Bxh6  does not give white more than a draw.  Nh5!  16.Qg5  Nf6  forcing white to repeat. Kh8 is the threat! }
15... cxd5 16. Bxh6
{ If White plays  16.Rd1  Black answers with the fantastic  Ra6!  , which is a profilactic move. If now white plays  17.Bxh6?  then  Nh5!  followed by Rxh6! }
16... Qb6
{ Now black does not need to go for the draw. Nh5 is a threat followed by Qxh6 and also the queen is targetting d4 and b2. }
17. Bg5 { only move to survive. } 17... Nxa4 18. Nxa4 Qxd4+ 19. Kh1 Be6 20. Nc3
Nh5 21. Qh4 Qxh4 22. Bxh4 Rac8
{ With a very healthy position. Black has an isolated pawn but enjoys pressure on the c-file and also White has some weak squares on the kingside. }
