{ The idea is to place the bishop on f8 and put pressure on e4. d5 is a very typical reaction in these positions. }
10. Ba2 { The mainline by far. It is a good prophylactic move against d5. }
10... Bf8 { and guess what? Yes, d5 is the idea. } 11. Qf3
{ White removes the queen from the e-file and keeps protecting the e4 pawn. Now we advocate two possibilities to continue. One is the main line and the second one is a super interesting novelty. }
11... Ne5 { The main line, activating the knight and hitting the queen. } 12.
Qg3
{ And at this point, we again suggest two different alternatives.   12...Nh5  is more solid and  12...Qb6  leads to crazy complications. }
12... Qb6
{ I like this move to play for the win. Many complications can arise from this pont. }
13. Rd1 { the best move, protecting the knight on d4. } 13... d5
{ fasten your seatbelt because curves are coming. } 14. exd5 Nh5
{ same idea chasing the queen. It is important to play d5 before Nh5 so the queen does not feel comfortable on the e-file. }
15. Qh4 Bg4 16. f3 Bc5 17. Be3 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Rxe3 19. Qxg4
{ it looks like white has managed to win a piece but } 19... Bxd4 20. a5
{ only move! It's so hard to understand chess! :@@EndBracket@@   20.Rxd4  runs into  Qxb2!-+ }
20... Qb4 21. Qxd4 Re1+ 22. Kf2 Qxd4+ 23. Rxd4 Rxa1 24. a6 c5 25. axb7 Rb8 26.
Rc4 Rxb7 { With an equal unbalanced position. } *

