1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. a5
{ Welcome to a new chapter!   I hope you are still full of energy to keep learning about my beloved Philidor defense!   8.a5  is a move that White plays to stop  8.--  8...a5  and to make it harder for black to play  8...b6  as well. We will try to push b5 soon, but to do that, we should first play }
8... Rb8
{ So we can push b5 and after white takes 'en passant', we can recapture with the a-pawn.   8...b5?!  is dubious because of  9.axb6  Nxb6  10.Bd3+=  and the structure favor White. }
9. Be3
{ Only 5 games in my database. In two of them, I was driving the black pieces. White targets the a7 pawn. }
9... b5 { Again and again this move :@@EndBracket@@ } 10. axb6 axb6 11. d5
{ With the same idea of installing a knight or a bishop on d5, but at this moment is risky for White. }
11... b5 12. Be2 b4 13. dxc6 bxc3 14. cxd7 Bxd7 15. bxc3 Nxe4
{ Black was much better in: NiTe90 @@StartBracket@@2889@@EndBracket@@-josecuenca @@StartBracket@@2893@@EndBracket@@ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com 2017.   White's pawn structure is just terrible. }
