1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. a5
{ Welcome to a new chapter!   I hope you are still full of energy to keep learning about my beloved Philidor defense!   8.a5  is a move that White plays to stop  8.--  8...a5  and to make it harder for black to play  8...b6  as well. We will try to push b5 soon, but to do that, we should first play }
8... Rb8
{ So we can push b5 and after white takes 'en passant', we can recapture with the a-pawn.   8...b5?!  is dubious because of  9.axb6  Nxb6  10.Bd3+=  and the structure favor White. }
9. h3 { A move that is played to control the g4 square. } 9... b5 10. axb6 axb6
11. Re1
{ 11.b4!?  is always interesting arriving at the same kind of positions that we saw in other lines. }
11... b5 12. Bf1 Bb7 13. b4 { as usual the most critical move. } 13... Ra8 14.
Rb1
{ 14.Rxa8  Qxa8  15.Be3  Re8=  with a solid position. Next move is Bf8 putting undirect pressure on e4. }
14... Re8 15. d5
{ leading to very complex positions where White will capture on b5 creating a passed pawn but in return Black will take the d5 pawn having a better center. }
15... cxd5 16. exd5 Qc8 17. Rb3 { this allows } 17... Ra1 18. Bxb5 Rd8
{ with this move black intends to play Nb6 and capture on d5. } 19. Qd3
{ 19.Bxd7  Nxd7=  This way White has managed to save the d5 pawn, but has given up the bishop pair, leading to an equal unbalanced position.   I would say this is very interesting to play for the win with the Black pieces.   Qa8 followed by Nb6 looks like a very decent plan to increase pressure on d5. }
19... Nb6 20. Bg5 Rxe1+ 21. Nxe1 Nbxd5 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ With mutual chances. White has a passed pawn but Black has an amazing center and a better bishop. }
*

