1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. a5
{ Welcome to a new chapter!   I hope you are still full of energy to keep learning about my beloved Philidor defense!   8.a5  is a move that White plays to stop  8.--  8...a5  and to make it harder for black to play  8...b6  as well. We will try to push b5 soon, but to do that, we should first play }
8... Rb8
{ So we can push b5 and after white takes 'en passant', we can recapture with the a-pawn.   8...b5?!  is dubious because of  9.axb6  Nxb6  10.Bd3+=  and the structure favor White. }
9. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most annoying one by far. White frees the d1-square for the rook. Now we give two different options to proceed. }
9... b5
{ this will be our second recommendation. It is the move that I have employed myself in every game where I faced this line. }
10. axb6 axb6 11. d5
{ This is white's idea. Now the queen is pointing to the c4 square. This is a very important subtlety. }
11... b5
{ This pawn sacrifice is in fact the first option from the engine. It leads to very forcing lines where black could hold with very precise play in a slightly worse position. It is not my cup of tea because we will barely have winning chances but definitely deserves some attention. }
12. dxc6 bxc4 13. cxd7 Bxd7
{ 13...Qxd7  14.Qxc4  Qb7  , with some compensation but White is better. } 14.
Qxc4 { White is a pawn up. Black has compensation because of the bishop pair. }
14... Be6 15. Qd3 Qc8 { Threatening Bc4 winning an exchange. } 16. b3
{ 16.Rd1!?+=  is also a normal choice for White.  h6  17.Ne1  Rd8  18.Qe3  Bg4  19.Rd3  Qc6+=  with Bh5 and Bg6 ideas. }
16... d5 17. Nxe5 dxe4 18. Nxe4 Rd8 19. Qe2 Nxe4 20. Qxe4 Bf6 21. Bf4 Bf5 22.
Qc4 Qxc4 23. Nxc4 Bxa1 24. Bxb8 Bxc2 25. Rxa1 Rxb8 26. Na5
{ And this is the position that I was talking about. Engines say Black can hold with very precise play, but definitely 0% winning chances and still a hard work to do for the draw. }
*

