1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. a5
{ Welcome to a new chapter!   I hope you are still full of energy to keep learning about my beloved Philidor defense!   8.a5  is a move that White plays to stop  8.--  8...a5  and to make it harder for black to play  8...b6  as well. We will try to push b5 soon, but to do that, we should first play }
8... Rb8
{ So we can push b5 and after white takes 'en passant', we can recapture with the a-pawn.   8...b5?!  is dubious because of  9.axb6  Nxb6  10.Bd3+=  and the structure favor White. }
9. Qe2
{ The mainline and the most annoying one by far. White frees the d1-square for the rook. Now we give two different options to proceed. }
9... exd4
{ This is going to be our first choice. It has been barely played, so it will probably come as a surprise to your opponent. It is also the first recommendation by Stockfish 12 in order to equalize. }
10. Nxd4 Re8
{ Whenever there is a queen on e2, it makes sense to bring a rook to e8, putting pressure on the e-file.   This position is very similar to the Chapter where white goes 8.Qe2, but a5 and Rb8 have been included which clearly favours white, since in many cases a bishop will come to f4 and will be hard for black to push d5. a7 will be under attack in many lines too.   Only two games in the database with this line. }
11. Ba2 Bf8 { d5 is threat now. } 12. Bf4
{ profilaxis against d5 using that the rook is on b8. } 12... Nc5 13. f3 Ne6
14. Be3 { the most critical line. } 14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 { targetting a7. }
15... b6
{ 15...a6  is also a decent choice aiming to go Be6 next move to fight against the super bishop on a2. }
16. axb6 axb6 17. Qc4 { 17.Rad1  b5= } 17... Qd7 18. Bxf6 gxf6
{ And we reach this position where Black's pawn structure is ruined but the bishop pair is powerful. b5 followed by f5 is coming with a very interesting and unbalanced position. }
