1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6
{ Hello everyone! In this chapter, we cover the rest of the secondary lines that White can play without including Re1.   Remember that 8.a5 and 8.Qe2 have their own chapters.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
8. dxe5
{ As we said many times, relaxing the tension in the center is not challenging for Black. }
8... dxe5
{ And the play is flexible from here, but you should know that the queen usually comes to c7 and a knight to c5.   a5 will be a good move very often to fix the pawn structure on the queenside.   Ne6 or Be6 will be also attractive once Black has played Nc5. }
9. Qe2 Qc7 10. Bg5 Nc5 11. h3 { Prophylaxis against Bg4. } 11... Ne6
{ Usually makes a lot of sense and now even more since there is a white bishop on g5. }
12. Be3
{ 12.Bxe6?!  has been played in several games but I think black is slightly better after  Bxe6  thanks to the bishop pair. }
12... Nh5
{ Looking for the f4 square.   12...h6  Is also possible  13.Rfd1  a5=  followed by Re8 }
13. Bxe6 { Is a better try for White. } 13... Bxe6 14. Ng5
{ Was seen in Vidic,S @@StartBracket@@2267@@EndBracket@@-Dumpor,A @@StartBracket@@2382@@EndBracket@@ Subotica 2004 and we deviate from the game with }
14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Nxe6 fxe6
{ And White should block on f3 and Black will continue placing the queen on e5 with a very healthy position. }
