1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6
{ Hello everyone! In this chapter, we cover the rest of the secondary lines that White can play without including Re1.   Remember that 8.a5 and 8.Qe2 have their own chapters.   No more talk and let's get to work! }
8. Bg5 h6 9. Be3 exd4
{ Black reacts in the usual way.   I think the inclusion of h6 favors Black since it is part of the plan anyway. }
10. Qxd4 Ng4 { Black looks for the e5 square. } 11. Bf4
{ White controls e5 with three pieces } 11... Nge5 { But anyway we go for it! }
12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Nxe5 Bc5 { Forcing White to play } 14. Nxf7 Rxf7 15. Bxf7+
Kxf7 16. Qc4+ Kf8
{ Reaching an equal and very double-edged position.   Black will play Qe7 followed by Nb6 and Be6 to complete development.   I usually tend two prefer the two pieces and even more if the bishop pair is alive, but of course, it is a matter of taste. }
