[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26.a) Main Line 7.Re1 followed by 8.a4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.Re1 and 8.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... b6
{ This is the main line by far and a move that I have been in love with since I was a kid.   I played more than 50 classical games with this line, but modern theory has shown that black cannot fully equalize in my opinion.   The line that annoys me the most is the following: }
9. Ba2 a6 10. h3 Rb8 11. Be3 b5 12. axb5 axb5 13. b4
{ And I tried very hard to find something suitable for Black in the last 2-3 years but I think White is just better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26.a) Main Line 7.Re1 followed by 8.a4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.Re1, 8.a4 and 9.a5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ Which is a secondary line.   Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it.   There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid.   Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move.   White has four main choices now. }
9. a5
{ Makes a lot of sense.   Black did not play b6 or a5 so white gains more space restricting black pieces on the queenside. }
9... Re8 10. d5
{ Now black has the strong reply   10.h3  Qc7  transposes to the lines analyzed after  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbpp1/2pp1n1p/4p3/P1BPP3/2N2N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  followed by  --  10.a5 }
10... b5 { A typical reaction in the Philidor. } 11. axb6 Nxb6
{ This is the key. The bishop on c4 is hanging.   Now Black is on time to fight for the d5 square. }
12. Bb3 cxd5 13. Nxd5
{ 13.exd5  a5  with the idea of Bd7-Qc7 and black has a very nice position. }
13... Nfxd5 14. exd5 Bg4
{ Black was slightly better in Perske,T @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@ -Predojevic,B @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ ½-½ Germany 2019.   All these positions where White cannot finally place a piece on d5 are great for Black.   There is a nasty pin on f3 that is not easy to handle for White. }
*

