{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ Which is a secondary line.   Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it.   There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid.   Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move.   White has four main choices now. }
9. Ba2
{ A very typical move, hiding the bishop in a safe square.   It is a prophylactic move against d5, b5 or even Nb6 ideas at some point. }
9... Re8 10. h3
{ The main line.   In fact we can reach this position as well after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbpp1/2pp1n1p/4p3/P1BPP3/2N2N2/1PP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  Re8  10.Ba2  White covers the g4 square so a bishop can land on e3 without troubles. }
10... a5 { Black fixes the structure on the queenside. } 11. Be3
{ This is the same position that Wesley So covers in his series but the white queen is on e2 and the bishop is on c4.   That tempo that White has lost by moving the bishop is very important for Black! }
11... exd4
{ A secondary line but the best move!   11...Qc7  Is the main line by far. }
12. Nxd4 Bf8
{ Improving the bishop and putting pressure on e4. White has tried four different moves now: }
13. Qf3 { Makes sense protecting e4 and connecting the rooks. } 13... Nc5
{ Black insists on e4. } 14. Bd2
{ And here we propose the novelty   14.Bf4  Transposes to the mainline analyzed after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/1p1n1pp1/2pp1n1p/p7/P2NP3/2N1B2P/BPP2PP1/R2QR1K1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Bf4 }
14... Ra6
{ A super interesting idea to play for the win!   Black wants to activate the rook via b6 and even place it on b4! }
15. Bc4
{ The best move! white wants to play b3 once the pawn is attacked and leave the bishop out of the pawn chain! }
15... Rb6 16. b3 Rb4
{ And the reader will not be able to avoid a smile.   What is that rook doing on b4?   It is super interesting and black is ready to give up the exchange on c4 if needed. }
17. Rad1 Ncd7
{ The bishop on c4 managed to be out of the pawn chain but of course it is more exposed.   Ne5 is the idea. }
18. Bf4 { Prophylaxis. White is ready to take on e5. } 18... d5
{ Boom!   Black creates chaos and the center is blown up. } 19. exd5 Rxe1+ 20.
Rxe1 Nb6 { The knight on d4 is unprotected. } 21. Qd3 Nxc4 22. bxc4 cxd5 23.
cxd5 Nxd5 24. Nde2 { There is a nasty pin along the d-file but Black holds. }
24... Be6 25. Bd2 Rb6 26. Nf4 Rd6 27. Nxe6 fxe6 28. Ne4 Rd7 29. Qf3 Rf7 30. Qg4
Nf6 31. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ And the bad pawn on e6 is compensated by the a4 and c2 weakneses on the queenside.   The position is about equal. }
