1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ Which is a secondary line.   Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it.   There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid.   Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move.   White has four main choices now. }
