1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone!   Welcome to a new chapter! In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means White goes for short castling, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a large number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ Which is a secondary line.   Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it.   There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid.   Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move.   White has four main choices now. }
9. h3 { The main continuation by far. } 9... Re8 10. a5
{ A very interesting move restricting Black play on the queenside. } 10... Qc7
{ And here white has many possibilities.   We deeply study all of them! } 11.
Ba2
{ Has been played in about 20 games.   a5 is always poissoned because of Bxf7 winning the queen.   11...Nf8  is the main line but I think black does not fully equalize, so we propose the novelty. }
11... Rb8 { With the idea of pushing b5. } 12. Nh4
{ I guess you are not surprised to see this move, right? It has been considered in almost every variation. White intends Nf5. }
12... Nf8 { 12...exd4  Has an important drawback now. The a7-pawn is hanging. }
13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qf3 Be6 15. Nf5 { 15.Be3  Ra8  16.Nf5  Transposes. } 15...
Bxa2 16. Rxa2 Ne6 { The knight protects g7 and puts an eye on d4. } 17. Be3
{ If  17.Qg3  Black can just play  Kh7 } 17... Ra8
{ The a-pawn must be protected. } 18. Raa1
{ Black had to waste a tempo with Ra8 but same story for white to bring the rook back to play.   Now I give you two decent options with which to proceed. }
18... b5 { Is interesting. } 19. Ne2 Ng5 20. Bxg5 hxg5 21. Neg3 g6 22. Nxe7+
Qxe7
{ The engines say white has a tiny edge @@StartBracket@@about 0.25 with depth 46@@EndBracket@@ but I think this is very playable and black is very solid.   Ideas: Kg7-Nd7-Nc5-Rad8. }
