1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
{ Hello everyone! Welcome to a new chapter!   In this occasion we will study the main line of the closed Philidor with 4...Nbd7.   That means white goes for short castle, followed by Re1 and a4.   Once you start playing the Philidor defence, you will face this line in a big number of occasions, so it is very important to know what we are doing here.   I bring some fresh ideas that hopefully will help you to get nice positions!. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6
{ Black threatens b5, starting a pawn march and kicking the bishop with a tempo. }
8. a4
{ White stops the queenside expansion. At this point we are going to recommend }
8... h6
{ Which is a secondary line.   Wesley So does not mention it in his e4 lifetime repertoire series, which means we can surprise the people who watched it.   There are some transpositions to lines studied in that series that we will avoid.   Black's idea is to cover the g5 square, so the rook can come to e8 in the next move. White has four main choices now. }
9. h3 { The main continuation by far. } 9... Re8 10. a5
{ A very interesting move restricting black play on the queenside. } 10... Qc7
{ And here White has many possibilities. We deeply study all of them! } 11. Be3
{ The main continuation.   White develops the last minor piece and prepares for connecting the rooks. }
11... exd4
{ This is our recommendation.   Great playes such as Bruzon, Kadric or Kunin have employed it.   11...Nf8  is again the main line, but I think white is clearly better. Another typical case of how main theory can evolve in chess. }
12. Bxd4 Ne5 13. Bb3 Bd8
{ The idea is to make a possible knight on h4 uncomfortable. Black intends to play Be6 to fight for the light squares.   13...Bf8?!  14.Nh4+-  and White is better. }
14. Nh4 { 14.Qe2  Be6  And Black has a healthy position. } 14... Nh7 15. Nf5
Bxf5 16. exf5 Bf6
{ With the idea of d5 or even Nd7, reaching a well known structure where Black is fine. }
