15. axb6 axb6 { Threatening b5 followed by b4. } 16. b4 b5 17. Bb3
{ Was seen in Gibson,T @@StartBracket@@2034@@EndBracket@@-Starodubtsev,V @@StartBracket@@2147@@EndBracket@@ ICCF ½-½ email 2016, where we propose the novelty }
17... Ne5
{ Reaching a very complicated position that needs to be studied in detail.   f4 followed by e5 will be always a dangerous idea that Black mus take into account.   Black will be patient and develop pieces step by step, waiting for a good opportunity to strike.   As you will see, c5 will be an idea.   The light squared bishop will land on b7 or d7 and the e5-knight will be placed on g6 most of the times. c4 is also a tasty square in certain variations. }
18. f4
{ The most direct approach, starting an attack on the kingside.   18.Kh1  Ng6  19.f4  transposes to  18.f4 }
18... Ng6
{ And here we have analyzed many different possibilities.   Try to pay attention because probably this is the most critical position of the whole chapter and where many tactical shots are present. }
19. Kh2
{ White removes the king from the a7-g1 diagonal. In all the lines where white tries e5, the king on h2 is not helping because after some Nf3 to increase the pressure against a possible black knight on e5, Nxf3 would come with check. }
19... Bb7 20. Qf3 { 20.Qd3  transposes } 20... Rbd8 21. Rad1 Qc8
{ This is a fantastic move! Black is now preparing c5. The key is that Nxb5 would not come with a tempo.   Black can also try Qa8 at some point increasing pressure against e4. }
22. Bf2 { 22.e5?  loses after  c5!-+ } 22... Qb8
{ Black queen targets f4 now. } 23. Bg3 Qc8 { Repetition } *

