{ We analyze now the three alternatives that White has chosen at this point. }
13. Bf4
{ Putting pressure on d6.   In fact white cannot capture since c4 is hanging and if white decides to take on e6 first, then the knight captures forking the queen and bishop. Therefore, black can continue preparing a queenside expansion with }
13... a6 14. Bh2 Rc8 15. Bf1
{ Finally white is threatening to take on d6, so Black should react with }
15... d5 16. Qa7 { 16.exd5?!  cxd5=+  Black has good play. Bc5 is coming. }
16... N8d7
{ Black is forced to sacrifice a pawn but in return the white queen will be in a very dangerous situation. }
17. Qxb7 Nc5 18. Qa7 Bf8
{ Ra8 is the threat and after a queen trade on c7, which is the only available square for the queen, e4 would be hanging. }
19. b4 Ra8 20. Qc7 Qxc7 21. Bxc7 Ncxe4 { As we just explained. } *

